{"title_page": "Zebroid", "text_new": "{{short description|Offspring of a zebra and any other equine}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Hybridbox\n| name     = Zebroid\n| image = Zorse.gif\n| image_alt = A zorse in an 1899 photograph, \"Romulus: one year old\", from J. C. Ewart's \"The Penycuik Experiments\"\n| image_caption = A zorse in an 1899 photograph, \"Romulus: one year old\", from J. C. Ewart's ''The Penycuik Experiments''\n| genus    = Equus\n| species1 = \"''zebra''\"\n| link1    = Zebra\n| species2 = \"''equine''\"\n| link2    = Equus (genus)\n}}\n\nA '''zebroid''' is the offspring of any cross between a [[zebra]] and any other [[equine]] to create a [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrid]]. In most cases, the sire is a zebra [[stallion]]. Offspring of a donkey sire and zebra dam called a '''donkra''' or '''zebra hinny''' and offspring of a horse sire and a zebra dam called a '''hebra''' do exist, but are rare and are usually sterile and infertile. Zebroids have been bred since the 19th century. [[Charles Darwin]] noted several zebra hybrids in his works.\n\n==Types==\nZebroid is the term generally used for all zebra hybrids. The different hybrids are generally named using a [[portmanteau]] of the [[wikt:sire#Noun|sire]]'s name and the [[wikt:dam#Noun 2|dam]]'s name. Generally, no distinction is made as to which zebra species is used. Many times, when zebras are crossbred, they develop some form of [[dwarfism]]. Breeding of different branches of the equine family, which does not occur in the wild, generally results in infertile offspring. The combination of sire and dam also affects the offspring [[phenotype]].\n\nA zorse is the offspring of a [[zebra]] stallion and a horse [[mare]]. This cross is also called a zebrula, zebrule, or zebra mule. The rarer reverse pairing is sometimes called a hebra, horbra, zebrinny, zebret, or zebra hinny. Like most other animal hybrids, the zorse is sterile.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.equinepost.com/resources/breeds/showBreed.asp?ID=150|title= Zorse Breed Description |work= Breeding References|publisher= EquinePost |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710195153/http://www.equinepost.com/resources/breeds/showBreed.asp?ID=150 |archivedate=2011-07-10}}</ref>\n\nA zony is the offspring of a zebra stallion and a pony mare. Medium-sized pony mares are preferred to produce riding zonies, but zebras have been crossed with smaller pony breeds such as the [[Shetland pony|Shetland]], resulting in so-called \"Zetlands\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Crisis-hit farm welcomes its gift forse|date= 27 June 2001 |quote=it could be a zorse perhaps, a fony, or maybe a shebra or a zetland. Whatever its name, the arrival of the strange beast has been hailed as a godsend|url=https://www.theguardian.com/silly/story/0,,530179,00.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Helen | last=Carter | accessdate=20 April 2010}}</ref>\n[[Image:Zeedonk 800.jpg|thumb|right|A zebra-donkey hybrid]]\n\nA cross between a zebra and a donkey is known by many terms, including: zonkey,<ref name=pri>{{cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2014-04-30/heres-everything-you-wanted-know-about-zonkeys-great-zebra-donkey-hybrids|title=Here's everything you wanted to know about zonkeys, the great zebra-donkey hybrids|website=Public Radio International}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=August 2019}} (a term also used for [[Zonkey (Tijuana)|donkeys in Tijuana]], [[Mexico]] painted as zebras for tourists to pose with them in souvenir photos)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/miranda/la-et-cam-story-behind-tijuana-zebra-striped-donkeys-20151106-column.html|title=How the zonkey got its stripes: Long before Instagram, Tijuana's tourist donkeys were camera-ready|first=Carolina A.|last=Miranda|website=latimes.com}}</ref> zebonkey, zebronkey, zebrinny, zebrula, zebrass, zedonk, and zebadonk. Donkeys are closely related to zebras and both animals belong to the [[Equidae|horse family]]. These zebra/donkey hybrids are very rare.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Megersa|first1=B|last2=Biffa|first2=D|last3=Kumsa|first3=B|title=A mysterious zebra-donkey hybrid (zedonk or zonkey) produced under natural mating: A case report from Borana, southern Ethiopia|journal=Animal Production Research Advances|date=13 February 2007|volume=2|issue=3|doi=10.4314/apra.v2i3.36328}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Benirschke|first1=K|last2=Low|first2=RJ|last3=Brownhill|first3=LE|last4=Caday|first4=LB|last5=Devenecia-Fernandez|first5=J|title=Chromosome Studies Of A Donkey-Grevy Zebra Hybrid|journal=Chromosoma|date=1 April 1964|volume=15|pages=1\u201313|doi=10.1007/BF00326911|pmid=14171168}}</ref> In [[South Africa]], they occur where zebras and donkeys are found in proximity to each other. Like [[mule]]s and [[hinny]]s, however, they are generally genetically unable to breed, due to an odd number of chromosomes disrupting [[meiosis]].\n\n==Genetics==\nLiving equids show wide variation in the number of [[chromosome]]s, ranging from a diploid number of 32 chromosomes in the [[mountain zebra]] to 66 in [[Przewalski's horse]]. This is due to number of chromosomal fusion and fission events during the evolution of equids.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Musilova|first=P.|last2=Kubickova|first2=S.|last3=Vahala|first3=J.|last4=Rubes|first4=J.|date=2013-03-27|title=Subchromosomal karyotype evolution in Equidae|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s10577-013-9346-z|journal=Chromosome Research|volume=21|issue=2|pages=175\u2013187|doi=10.1007/s10577-013-9346-z|issn=0967-3849}}</ref> The zebra has between 32 and 46 chromosomes depending on the species.\n\nIn spite of this difference, viable hybrids are possible, provided the gene combination in the hybrid allows for embryonic development to birth. A hybrid has a number of chromosomes somewhere in between. The chromosome difference makes female hybrids poorly fertile and male hybrids generally sterile, due to a phenomenon called [[Haldane's rule]]. The difference in chromosome number is most likely due to horses having two longer chromosomes that contain similar gene content to four zebra chromosomes.<ref>{{Cite journal | title = Chromosome Studies of a Donkey-Grevy Zebra Hybrid | journal = Chromosoma | volume = 15 | issue = 1 | year = 1964 | author = K. Benirschke |display-authors=et al | pmid=14171168 | doi = 10.1007/BF00326911 | pages = 1\u201313}}</ref> Horses have 64 chromosomes, while most zebroids end up with 54 chromosomes.\nJust as male mules and hinnies are infertile so are male zebroids. And just as female mules and hinnies only very rarely produce offspring the same appears to be true of zebroids. Considering zebroids are much less common as mules the chances of a fertile zebroid mare are very slim. Only ONE case of such a mare was reported : The zebroid mare of a zebra mare x draft horse stallion produced a foal when she was bred back to her sire but the foal died of lightning and she did not survive it much longer.\n\n=== Extant ''Equus'' species: chromosome number ===\n{{See also|Equus (genus)#Taxonomic_and_evolutionary_history}}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\"\n!Subgenus\n!Scientific name\n!Common name\n!Chromosome number (2n)\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" |''Hippotigris''\n\n(Zebras)\n|''Equus zebra''\n|[[Mountain zebra]]\n|32\n|-\n|''Equus grevyi''\n|[[Gr\u00e9vy's zebra]]\n|46\n|-\n|''Equus quagga''\n|[[Plains zebra]]\n|44\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" |'''''Asinus'''''\n\n'''(wild asses)'''\n|''Equus africanus''\n|[[African wild ass]]; includes domesticated [[donkey]]\n|62\n|-\n|''Equus hemionus''\n|[[Onager]], hemione, or Asiatic wild ass\n|56\n|-\n|''Equus kiang''\n|[[Kiang]]\n|52 <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=J\u00f3nsson|first=H\u00e1kon|last2=Schubert|first2=Mikkel|last3=Seguin-Orlando|first3=Andaine|last4=Ginolhac|first4=Aur\u00e9lien|last5=Petersen|first5=Lillian|last6=Fumagalli|first6=Matteo|last7=Albrechtsen|first7=Anders|last8=Petersen|first8=Bent|last9=Korneliussen|first9=Thorfinn S.|last10=Vilstrup|first10=Julia T.|last11=Lear|first11=Teri|date=2014-12-30|title=Speciation with gene flow in equids despite extensive chromosomal plasticity|url=http://www.pnas.org/lookup/doi/10.1073/pnas.1412627111|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=111|issue=52|pages=18655\u201318660|doi=10.1073/pnas.1412627111|issn=0027-8424|pmc=4284605|pmid=25453089}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |''Equus''\n|''Equus ferus caballus''\n|Domesticated [[horse]]\n|64\n|-\n|''Equus ferus przewalskii''\n|[[Przewalski's horse]]\n|66 <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lau|first=Allison N.|last2=Peng|first2=Lei|last3=Goto|first3=Hiroki|last4=Chemnick|first4=Leona|last5=Ryder|first5=Oliver A.|last6=Makova|first6=Kateryna D.|date=2009-01-01|title=Horse Domestication and Conservation Genetics of Przewalski's Horse Inferred from Sex Chromosomal and Autosomal Sequences|url=https://academic.oup.com/mbe/article/26/1/199/973911|journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=199\u2013208|doi=10.1093/molbev/msn239|issn=0737-4038}}</ref>\n|}\nZebras are more closely related to wild asses (a group which includes donkeys) than to horses. The horse lineage diverged from other equids an estimated 4.0 - 4.7 million years ago;<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Vilstrup|first=Julia T.|last2=Seguin-Orlando|first2=Andaine|last3=Stiller|first3=Mathias|last4=Ginolhac|first4=Aurelien|last5=Raghavan|first5=Maanasa|last6=Nielsen|first6=Sandra C. A.|last7=Weinstock|first7=Jacobo|last8=Froese|first8=Duane|last9=Vasiliev|first9=Sergei K.|last10=Ovodov|first10=Nikolai D.|last11=Clary|first11=Joel|date=2013-02-20|editor-last=Lalueza-Fox|editor-first=Carles|title=Mitochondrial Phylogenomics of Modern and Ancient Equids|url=https://dx.plos.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0055950|journal=PLoS ONE|language=en|volume=8|issue=2|pages=e55950|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0055950|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3577844|pmid=23437078}}</ref> zebras and asses  diverged an estimated 1.69\u20131.99 million years ago.<ref name=\":0\" /> The cladogram of ''Equus'' below is simplified from Vistrup ''et al.'' (2013).<ref name=\":1\" />{{clade| style=font-size:85%; line-height:90%;\n|label1=''Equus''\n|1={{clade\n |1={{clade\n|label2=\n  |1={{clade\n |label1=Zebras\n |label2=Wild asses\n   |1={{clade\n    |1=[[Mountain zebra]] (''E. zebra'')\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=[[Plains zebra]] (''E. quagga'')\n     |2=[[Gr\u00e9vy's zebra]] (''E. grevyi'')}} }}\n   |2={{clade\n    |1={{clade\n     |1=[[Kiang]] (''E. kiang'')\n     |2=[[Onager]] (''E. hemionus'') }}\n    |2=[[African wild ass]] (''E. africanus'') }} }} }}\n  |label2=Horses\n |2={{clade\n    |1=[[Horse]] (''E. ferus caballus'')\n    |2=[[Przewalski's horse]] (''E. ferus przewalski'') }} }} }}\n\n==Physical characteristics==\n[[File:Z\u00e9brulecouch\u00e9.jpg|thumb|left|A zorse]]\nZebroids physically resemble their nonzebra parent, but are striped like a zebra. The stripes generally do not cover the whole body, and might be confined to the legs or spread onto parts of the body or neck. If the nonzebra parent was patterned (such as a [[Roan (horse)|roan]], [[Appaloosa]], [[Pinto horse|pinto]]/[[American Paint Horse|paint]], [[piebald]], or [[skewbald]]), this pattern might be passed down to the zebroid, in which case the stripes are usually confined to non-white areas. The alternative name \"golden zebra\" relates to the interaction of zebra striping and a horse's bay or chestnut colour to give a zebra-like black-on-bay or black-on-chestnut pattern that superficially resembles the extinct [[quagga]]. Zebra-donkey hybrids usually have a dorsal (back) stripe and a ventral (belly) stripe.\n\n[[File:Zorse.jpg|thumb|The hebra Eclyse]]\nZorses combine the zebra striping overlaid on colored areas of the hybrid's coat. Zorses are most often bred using solid-color horses. If the horse parent is piebald (black and white) or skewbald (other color and white), the zorse may inherit the dominant depigmentation genes for white patches. The [[tobiano]] (the most common white modifier found in the horse) directly interacts with the zorse coat to give the white markings. Only the nondepigmented areas will have zebra striping, resulting in a zorse with white patches and striped patches. This effect is seen in the zebroid named Eclyse (a hebra rather than a zorse) born in Stukenbrock, Germany, in 2007 to a zebra mare called Eclipse and a stallion called Ulysses.\n\nZebroids are preferred over zebras for practical uses, such as riding, because the zebra has a different body shape from a [[horse]] or [[donkey]], and consequently it is difficult to find [[Horse tack|tack]] to fit a zebra. However, a zebroid is usually more inclined to be temperamental than a [[purebred]] horse and can be difficult to handle. Zebras, being wild animals, and not domesticated like horses and donkeys, pass on their wild animal traits to their offspring.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} Zebras, while not usually very large, are extremely strong and aggressive. Similarly, zorses have a strong temperament and can be aggressive.\n\n==Historical and notable zebroids==\n[[Image:zebroidfoal.jpg|thumbnail|Zebra-horse hybrid foal with quagga-like markings, [[Walter Rothschild Zoological Museum]], [[Tring]], [[England]]]]\n\nIn 1815, Lord Morton mated a quagga stallion to a chestnut [[Arabian horse|Arabian]] mare. The result was a female hybrid which resembled both parents. This provoked the interest of Cossar Ewart, Professor of Natural History at Edinburgh (1882\u20131927) and a keen geneticist. Ewart crossed a zebra stallion with pony mares to investigate the theory of [[telegony (pregnancy)|telegony]], or paternal impression. In ''[[Origin of Species]]'' (1859), [[Charles Darwin]] mentioned four coloured drawings of hybrids between the ass and zebra. He also wrote\n<blockquote>\nIn Lord Morton's famous hybrid from a chestnut mare and male quagga, the hybrid, and even the pure offspring subsequently produced from the mare by a black Arabian sire, were much more plainly barred across the legs than is even the pure quagga.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Darwin|first1=Charles|title=On the origin of species, 1859.|date=2009|publisher=New York University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0814720585|pages=118\u2013119}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\nIn his book ''[[The Variation of Animals and Plants under Domestication]]'', Darwin described a hybrid ass-zebra specimen in the British Museum as being dappled on its flanks. He also mentioned a \"triple hybrid, from a bay mare, by a hybrid from a male ass and female zebra\" displayed at [[London Zoo]]. This would have required the zebroid sire to be fertile.\n\nDuring the South African War, the [[Boer]]s crossed Chapman's zebras with ponies, to produce animals for transport work, chiefly for hauling guns. A specimen was captured by British forces and presented to [[King Edward VII]] by [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Lord Kitchener]], and was photographed by W. S. Berridge.<ref>''Wonders of Animal Life'', edited by [[John Alexander Hammerton|J. A. Hammerton]] (1930)</ref> Zebras are resistant to sleeping sickness, whereas purebred horses and ponies are not, and  zebra mules hopefully would inherit this resistance.\n\nGrevy's zebra has been crossed with the [[Somali wild ass]] in the early 20th century. [[Zorse]]s were bred by the US government and reported in ''Genetics in Relation to Agriculture'' by E. B. Babcock and R. E. Clausen (early 20th century), in an attempt to investigate inheritance and telegony. The experiments were also reported in ''The Science of Life'' by H G Wells, J Huxley, and G P Wells (around 1929).\n\nInterest in zebra crosses continued in the 1970s. In 1973, a cross between a zebra and a donkey was foaled at the Jerusalem Zoo. They called it a \"hamzab\". In the 1970s, the [[Colchester Zoo]] in England bred zedonks, at first by accident and later to create a disease-resistant riding and draft animal. The experiment was discontinued when zoos became more conservation-minded. A number of hybrids were kept at the zoo after this; the last died in 2009.<ref>{{cite press release| title = Colchester Zoo mourns the loss of Shadow the Zeedonk| url = http://www.colchester-zoo.com/index.cfm?fa=news.press.detail&Press_Release_ID=244| date = 3 April 2009| publisher = Colchester Zoo| url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110708174954/http://www.colchester-zoo.com/index.cfm?fa=news.press.detail&Press_Release_ID=244| archivedate = 8 July 2011| df = dmy-all}}</ref> One adult still remains at the tourist attraction of [[Groombridge Place]]<ref>{{cite web |title=The Enchanted Forest |url=http://www.groombridge.co.uk/enchanted.htm |work=Groombridge Place Gardens |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729084438/http://www.groombridge.co.uk/enchanted.htm |archivedate=29 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> near Tunbridge Wells in Kent.\n\n===21st century===\nToday, various zebroids are bred as riding and draft animals, and as curiosities in circuses and smaller zoos. Zorses are bred in Africa and used for trekking on [[Mount Kenya]];<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-464723/Meet-Eclyse--amazing-zebra-crossing.html|title= Meet Eclyse - the amazing zebra crossing|accessdate= 10 July 2008|work= Mail Online|publisher= Associated Newspapers Ltd|location= London|date= 28 June 2007|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://archive.today/20120729061248/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-464723/Meet-Eclyse--amazing-zebra-crossing.html|archivedate= 29 July 2012|df= dmy-all}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=September 2019}} the zebra parent gives resistance to the [[nagana pest]] disease. A zorse (more accurately a zony) was born at Eden Ostrich World, [[Cumbria]], England, in 2001, after a zebra was left in a field with a Shetland pony. It was referred to as a Zetland. Usually, a zebra stallion is paired with a horse mare or donkey mare, but in 2005, a [[Burchell's zebra]] named Allison produced a zonkey called Alex sired by a donkey at Highland Plantation in the parish of [[Saint Thomas, Barbados]]. Alex, born 21 April 2005, is apparently the first zonkey in Barbados.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Call it zonkey or a deebra? Zebra has a foal sired by a donkey |agency=Associated Press |publisher=NBC News |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/7677651 |date=29 Apr 2005 |accessdate=13 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2007, a stallion, Ulysses, and a zebra mare, Eclipse, produced a hebra named Eclyse, displaying an unusually patchy color coating.<ref>Amanda Billner. [http://www.dn.se/DNet/jsp/polopoly.jsp?d=148&a=665762 \"Zebran \u00e4r en h\u00e4st\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930184652/http://www.dn.se/DNet/jsp/polopoly.jsp?d=148&a=665762 |date=30 September 2007 }} (in Swedish). ''[[Dagens Nyheter]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s webpage, 28 June 2007. Retrieved 30 June 2007.</ref><ref>BBC [http://news.bbc.co.uk/player/nol/newsid_6260000/newsid_6263900/6263928.stm?bw=bb&mp=rm \"Half horse, half zebra - hebra] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904170507/http://news.bbc.co.uk/player/nol/newsid_6260000/newsid_6263900/6263928.stm?bw=bb&mp=rm |date=4 September 2007 }} Retrieved 3 July 2007]</ref> The Wild Animal Safari in [[Springfield, Missouri]], and its sister location in [[Pine Mountain, Harris County, Georgia|Pine Mountain, Georgia]], have several zonkeys as of 31 March 2010.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} In July 2010, a zonkey was born at the Chestatee Wildlife Preserve in Dahlonega, Georgia.<ref>{{cite web | title=Zebra, donkey hybrid born in Dahlonega | url=http://www.gainesvilletimes.com/section/6/article/35810/ | date=27 July 2010 | publisher=Gainesville Times}}</ref> Another zebra\u2013donkey hybrid, like the Barbados zonkey sired by a donkey, was born 3 July 2011 in Haicang Safari Park, [[Haicang Town|Haicang]], [[Xiamen]], China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Donkra: Cross between Donkey, Zebra born |publisher=[[3 News]] |date=5 July 2011 |url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Donkra-Cross-between-Donkey-Zebra-born/tabid/1160/articleID/217643/}}</ref> A zonkey, Ippo, was born 21 July 2013 in an animal reserve, in [[Florence]], [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite news | title=It\u2019s a zonkey! Zebra and donkey hybrid born in Italy | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/zonkey-zebra-donkey-hybrid-born-italy-article-1.1407688 | location=New York | work=Daily News | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727142326/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/zonkey-zebra-donkey-hybrid-born-italy-article-1.1407688 | archivedate=27 July 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Khumba, the offspring of a zebra dam and a dwarf [[Albinism#Other animals|albino]] donkey sire, was born on 21 April 2014 in the zoo of [[Reynosa]] in the state of [[Tamaulipas, Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Zonkey born in a zoo in Mexico |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/centralamericaandthecaribbean/mexico/10787551/Zonkey-born-in-a-zoo-in-Mexico.html |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=25 April 2014 |accessdate=26 April 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426024800/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/centralamericaandthecaribbean/mexico/10787551/Zonkey-born-in-a-zoo-in-Mexico.html |archivedate=26 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> More recently, in November 2018 at a farm in Somerset, a cross between a donkey stallion and a zebra mare was born.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/donkey-zebra-cross-born-uk-britain-somerset-farm-south-barrow-a8617931.html|title=Rare cross between donkey and zebra known as \u2018zonkey\u2019 born on Somerset farm|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-11-06|language=en-GB}}</ref> The male foal was described as a zonkey by its owner and has been named Zippy.\n\n==Popular culture==\nZorses have appeared in several TV shows and movies. In the ''[[Viva La Bam]]'' episode \"Groundhog Day\". in the final race, [[Brandon Dicamillo]]'s sled is a zorse. It was colored pink, blue, purple. and red. On the 'uncommentary' on the DVD seasons of ''Viva La Bam'', Tim Glomb says, \"If you send me a list of all the episodes where the zorse is, I'll give you a dollar\". The 2007 movie ''[[I'm Reed Fish]]'' features a zorse named Zabrina. In the movie ''[[Racing Stripes]]'', an animated zorse appears in the alternate ending. He is the son of Stripes, a zebra [[stallion]] and Sandy, a grey Arabian mare.\n\nZorses have also appeared in books. They are briefly mentioned several times in [[George R.R. Martin]]'s ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' series of fantasy novels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awoiaf.westeros.org/index.php/Zorse|title=Zorse|website=westeros.org|accessdate=6 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20160313033540/http://awoiaf.westeros.org/index.php/Zorse|archivedate=13 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sutton Coleman wrote a sonnet about zorses and published it in his 2007 book, ''[[Ligers]], [[Tigons]], and Zorses, Oh My!'' In [[Roald Dahl]]'s book ''[[Going Solo]]'',  several other characters and he speculate on how nice it would be to own a zorse, although they admit it would be difficult to [[domestication of animals|train]].\n\nThe fantasy setting ''[[Glorantha]]'' has a magical fertile breed of horses crossed with zebras based on the city of Pavis. This small population is extended by breeding stallions of these breeds with ordinary horses, creating an infertile breed called Cavalry Zebras.\n \nThe video game ''[[Red Dead Redemption]]'' has the \"Zebra Donkey\" available as a multiplayer mount.\n\nIn ''[[El Tigre: The Adventures of Manny Rivera]]'', the characters' school's mascot is the famed Zebra Donkey.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Zorses}}\n*[http://www.messybeast.com/genetics/hybrid-equines.htm Hybrid Equines] Information and images of different zebroids\n*[http://photos1.blogger.com/x/blogger2/6012/701/600/z/85488/gse_multipart23028.jpg Eclyse] - Photo of a zebroid named Eclyse\n*{{cite news |title=Zenkey foal a hybrid star |date=29 Aug 2003 |work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/08/28/1062050609625.html }}\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/1408717.stm BBC News (26 June 2001): \"Zebra Hybrid is Cute Surprise\"]\n*[http://www.metro.co.uk/weird/article.html?in_article_id=54968 Metro (28 June 2007): \"A single-zorsed story\"]\n*Dorsett, Katherine. \"[http://www.cnn.com/2010/US/09/23/what.is.zedonk/index.html What the heck is a zedonk?]\" ''[[CNN]]''. 23 September 2010.\n*[http://www.izzza.com The International Zebra Zorse Zonkey Association ]\n*[http://www.educatedearth.net/video.php?id=3559 Video of a Zorse]\n*[http://www.ansa.it/web/notizie/rubriche/english/2013/07/22/Rare-zebra-donkey-mix-born-Florence-animal-reserve_9059572.html Rare zebra-donkey mix born in Florence animal reserve: The zonkey named Ippo only one in Italy]\n\n{{Mammal hybrids|state=collapsed}}\n{{equine|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Equid hybrids]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Offspring of a zebra and any other equine}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Hybridbox\n| name     = Zebroid\n| image = Zorse.gif\n| image_alt = A zorse in an 1899 photograph, \"Romulus: one year old\", from J. C. Ewart's \"The Penycuik Experiments\"\n| image_caption = A zorse in an 1899 photograph, \"Romulus: one year old\", from J. C. Ewart's ''The Penycuik Experiments''\n| genus    = Equus\n| species1 = \"''zebra''\"\n| link1    = Zebra\n| species2 = \"''equine''\"\n| link2    = Equus (genus)\n}}\n\nA '''zebroid''' is the offspring of any cross between a [[zebra]] and any other [[equine]] to create a [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrid]]. In most cases, the sire is a zebra [[stallion]]. Offspring of a donkey sire and zebra dam called a '''donkra''' or '''zebra hinny''' and offspring of a horse sire and a zebra dam called a '''hebra''' do exist, but are rare and are usually sterile and infertile. Zebroids have been bred since the 19th century. [[Charles Darwin]] noted several zebra hybrids in his works.\n\n==Types==\nZebroid is the term generally used for all zebra hybrids. The different hybrids are generally named using a [[portmanteau]] of the [[wikt:sire#Noun|sire]]'s name and the [[wikt:dam#Noun 2|dam]]'s name. Generally, no distinction is made as to which zebra species is used. Many times, when zebras are crossbred, they develop some form of [[dwarfism]]. Breeding of different branches of the equine family, which does not occur in the wild, generally results in infertile offspring. The combination of sire and dam also affects the offspring [[phenotype]].\n\nA zorse is the offspring of a [[zebra]] stallion and a horse [[mare]]. This cross is also called a zebrula, zebrule, or zebra mule. The rarer reverse pairing is sometimes called a hebra, horbra, zebrinny, zebret, or zebra hinny. Like most other animal hybrids, the zorse is sterile.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.equinepost.com/resources/breeds/showBreed.asp?ID=150|title= Zorse Breed Description |work= Breeding References|publisher= EquinePost |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710195153/http://www.equinepost.com/resources/breeds/showBreed.asp?ID=150 |archivedate=2011-07-10}}</ref>\n\nA zony is the offspring of a zebra stallion and a pony mare. Medium-sized pony mares are preferred to produce riding zonies, but zebras have been crossed with smaller pony breeds such as the [[Shetland pony|Shetland]], resulting in so-called \"Zetlands\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Crisis-hit farm welcomes its gift forse|date= 27 June 2001 |quote=it could be a zorse perhaps, a fony, or maybe a shebra or a zetland. Whatever its name, the arrival of the strange beast has been hailed as a godsend|url=https://www.theguardian.com/silly/story/0,,530179,00.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Helen | last=Carter | accessdate=20 April 2010}}</ref>\n[[Image:Zeedonk 800.jpg|thumb|right|A zebra-donkey hybrid]]\n\nA cross between a zebra and a donkey is known by many terms, including: zonkey,<ref name=pri>{{cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2014-04-30/heres-everything-you-wanted-know-about-zonkeys-great-zebra-donkey-hybrids|title=Here's everything you wanted to know about zonkeys, the great zebra-donkey hybrids|website=Public Radio International}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=August 2019}} (a term also used for [[Zonkey (Tijuana)|donkeys in Tijuana]], [[Mexico]] painted as zebras for tourists to pose with them in souvenir photos)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/miranda/la-et-cam-story-behind-tijuana-zebra-striped-donkeys-20151106-column.html|title=How the zonkey got its stripes: Long before Instagram, Tijuana's tourist donkeys were camera-ready|first=Carolina A.|last=Miranda|website=latimes.com}}</ref> zebonkey, zebronkey, zebrinny, zebrula, zebrass, zedonk, and zebadonk. Donkeys are closely related to zebras and both animals belong to the [[Equidae|horse family]]. These zebra/donkey hybrids are very rare.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Megersa|first1=B|last2=Biffa|first2=D|last3=Kumsa|first3=B|title=A mysterious zebra-donkey hybrid (zedonk or zonkey) produced under natural mating: A case report from Borana, southern Ethiopia|journal=Animal Production Research Advances|date=13 February 2007|volume=2|issue=3|doi=10.4314/apra.v2i3.36328}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Benirschke|first1=K|last2=Low|first2=RJ|last3=Brownhill|first3=LE|last4=Caday|first4=LB|last5=Devenecia-Fernandez|first5=J|title=Chromosome Studies Of A Donkey-Grevy Zebra Hybrid|journal=Chromosoma|date=1 April 1964|volume=15|pages=1\u201313|doi=10.1007/BF00326911|pmid=14171168}}</ref> In [[South Africa]], they occur where zebras and donkeys are found in proximity to each other. Like [[mule]]s and [[hinny]]s, however, they are generally genetically unable to breed, due to an odd number of chromosomes disrupting [[meiosis]].\n\n==Genetics==\nLiving equids show wide variation in the number of [[chromosome]]s, ranging from a diploid number of 32 chromosomes in the [[mountain zebra]] to 66 in [[Przewalski's horse]]. This is due to number of chromosomal fusion and fission events during the evolution of equids.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Musilova|first=P.|last2=Kubickova|first2=S.|last3=Vahala|first3=J.|last4=Rubes|first4=J.|date=2013-03-27|title=Subchromosomal karyotype evolution in Equidae|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s10577-013-9346-z|journal=Chromosome Research|volume=21|issue=2|pages=175\u2013187|doi=10.1007/s10577-013-9346-z|issn=0967-3849}}</ref> The zebra has between 32 and 46 chromosomes depending on the species.\n\nIn spite of this difference, viable hybrids are possible, provided the gene combination in the hybrid allows for embryonic development to birth. A hybrid has a number of chromosomes somewhere in between. The chromosome difference makes female hybrids poorly fertile and male hybrids generally sterile, due to a phenomenon called [[Haldane's rule]]. The difference in chromosome number is most likely due to horses having two longer chromosomes that contain similar gene content to four zebra chromosomes.<ref>{{Cite journal | title = Chromosome Studies of a Donkey-Grevy Zebra Hybrid | journal = Chromosoma | volume = 15 | issue = 1 | year = 1964 | author = K. Benirschke |display-authors=et al | pmid=14171168 | doi = 10.1007/BF00326911 | pages = 1\u201313}}</ref> Horses have 64 chromosomes, while most zebroids end up with 54 chromosomes.\nJust as male mules and hinnies are infertile so are male zebroids. And just as female mules and hinnies only very rarely produce offspring the same appears to be true of zebroids. Considering zebroids are much less common as mules the chances of a fertile zebroid mare are very slim. Only ONE case of such a mare was reported : The zebroid mare of a zebra mare x draft horse stallion produced a foal when she was bred back to her sire but the foal died of lightning and she did not survive it much longer.\n\n=== Extant ''Equus'' species: chromosome number ===\n{{See also|Equus (genus)#Taxonomic_and_evolutionary_history}}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\"\n!Subgenus\n!Scientific name\n!Common name\n!Chromosome number (2n)\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" |''Hippotigris''\n\n(Zebras)\n|''Equus zebra''\n|[[Mountain zebra]]\n|32\n|-\n|''Equus grevyi''\n|[[Gr\u00e9vy's zebra]]\n|46\n|-\n|''Equus quagga''\n|[[Plains zebra]]\n|44\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" |'''''Asinus''''' \n\n'''(wild asses)'''\n|''Equus africanus''\n|[[African wild ass]]; includes domesticated [[donkey]]\n|62\n|-\n|''Equus hemionus''\n|[[Onager]], hemione, or Asiatic wild ass\n|56\n|-\n|''Equus kiang''\n|[[Kiang]]\n|52 <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=J\u00f3nsson|first=H\u00e1kon|last2=Schubert|first2=Mikkel|last3=Seguin-Orlando|first3=Andaine|last4=Ginolhac|first4=Aur\u00e9lien|last5=Petersen|first5=Lillian|last6=Fumagalli|first6=Matteo|last7=Albrechtsen|first7=Anders|last8=Petersen|first8=Bent|last9=Korneliussen|first9=Thorfinn S.|last10=Vilstrup|first10=Julia T.|last11=Lear|first11=Teri|date=2014-12-30|title=Speciation with gene flow in equids despite extensive chromosomal plasticity|url=http://www.pnas.org/lookup/doi/10.1073/pnas.1412627111|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=111|issue=52|pages=18655\u201318660|doi=10.1073/pnas.1412627111|issn=0027-8424|pmc=4284605|pmid=25453089}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |''Equus''\n|''Equus ferus caballus''\n|Domesticated [[horse]]\n|64\n|-\n|''Equus ferus przewalskii''\n|[[Przewalski's horse]]\n|66 <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lau|first=Allison N.|last2=Peng|first2=Lei|last3=Goto|first3=Hiroki|last4=Chemnick|first4=Leona|last5=Ryder|first5=Oliver A.|last6=Makova|first6=Kateryna D.|date=2009-01-01|title=Horse Domestication and Conservation Genetics of Przewalski's Horse Inferred from Sex Chromosomal and Autosomal Sequences|url=https://academic.oup.com/mbe/article/26/1/199/973911|journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution|language=en|volume=26|issue=1|pages=199\u2013208|doi=10.1093/molbev/msn239|issn=0737-4038}}</ref>\n|}\nZebras are more closely related to wild asses (a group which includes donkeys) than to horses. The horse lineage diverged from other equids an estimated 4.0 - 4.7 million years ago;<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Vilstrup|first=Julia T.|last2=Seguin-Orlando|first2=Andaine|last3=Stiller|first3=Mathias|last4=Ginolhac|first4=Aurelien|last5=Raghavan|first5=Maanasa|last6=Nielsen|first6=Sandra C. A.|last7=Weinstock|first7=Jacobo|last8=Froese|first8=Duane|last9=Vasiliev|first9=Sergei K.|last10=Ovodov|first10=Nikolai D.|last11=Clary|first11=Joel|date=2013-02-20|editor-last=Lalueza-Fox|editor-first=Carles|title=Mitochondrial Phylogenomics of Modern and Ancient Equids|url=https://dx.plos.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0055950|journal=PLoS ONE|language=en|volume=8|issue=2|pages=e55950|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0055950|issn=1932-6203|pmc=PMC3577844|pmid=23437078}}</ref> zebras and asses  diverged an estimated 1.69\u20131.99 million years ago.<ref name=\":0\" /> The cladogram of ''Equus'' below is simplified from Vistrup ''et al.'' (2013). <ref name=\":1\" />{{clade| style=font-size:85%; line-height:90%;\n|label1=''Equus''\n|1={{clade\n |1={{clade\n|label2=\n  |1={{clade\n |label1=Zebras\n |label2=Wild asses\n   |1={{clade\n    |1=[[Mountain zebra]] (''E. zebra'')\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=[[Plains zebra]] (''E. quagga'')\n     |2=[[Gr\u00e9vy's zebra]] (''E. grevyi'')}} }}\n   |2={{clade\n    |1={{clade\n     |1=[[Kiang]] (''E. kiang'')\n     |2=[[Onager]] (''E. hemionus'') }}\n    |2=[[African wild ass]] (''E. africanus'') }} }} }}\n  |label2=Horses\n |2={{clade\n    |1=[[Horse]] (''E. ferus caballus'')\n    |2=[[Przewalski's horse]] (''E. ferus przewalski'') }} }} }}\n\n==Physical characteristics==\n[[File:Z\u00e9brulecouch\u00e9.jpg|thumb|left|A zorse]]\nZebroids physically resemble their nonzebra parent, but are striped like a zebra. The stripes generally do not cover the whole body, and might be confined to the legs or spread onto parts of the body or neck. If the nonzebra parent was patterned (such as a [[Roan (horse)|roan]], [[Appaloosa]], [[Pinto horse|pinto]]/[[American Paint Horse|paint]], [[piebald]], or [[skewbald]]), this pattern might be passed down to the zebroid, in which case the stripes are usually confined to non-white areas. The alternative name \"golden zebra\" relates to the interaction of zebra striping and a horse's bay or chestnut colour to give a zebra-like black-on-bay or black-on-chestnut pattern that superficially resembles the extinct [[quagga]]. Zebra-donkey hybrids usually have a dorsal (back) stripe and a ventral (belly) stripe.\n\n[[File:Zorse.jpg|thumb|The hebra Eclyse]]\nZorses combine the zebra striping overlaid on colored areas of the hybrid's coat. Zorses are most often bred using solid-color horses. If the horse parent is piebald (black and white) or skewbald (other color and white), the zorse may inherit the dominant depigmentation genes for white patches. The [[tobiano]] (the most common white modifier found in the horse) directly interacts with the zorse coat to give the white markings. Only the nondepigmented areas will have zebra striping, resulting in a zorse with white patches and striped patches. This effect is seen in the zebroid named Eclyse (a hebra rather than a zorse) born in Stukenbrock, Germany, in 2007 to a zebra mare called Eclipse and a stallion called Ulysses.\n\nZebroids are preferred over zebras for practical uses, such as riding, because the zebra has a different body shape from a [[horse]] or [[donkey]], and consequently it is difficult to find [[Horse tack|tack]] to fit a zebra. However, a zebroid is usually more inclined to be temperamental than a [[purebred]] horse and can be difficult to handle. Zebras, being wild animals, and not domesticated like horses and donkeys, pass on their wild animal traits to their offspring.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} Zebras, while not usually very large, are extremely strong and aggressive. Similarly, zorses have a strong temperament and can be aggressive.\n\n==Historical and notable zebroids==\n[[Image:zebroidfoal.jpg|thumbnail|Zebra-horse hybrid foal with quagga-like markings, [[Walter Rothschild Zoological Museum]], [[Tring]], [[England]]]]\n\nIn 1815, Lord Morton mated a quagga stallion to a chestnut [[Arabian horse|Arabian]] mare. The result was a female hybrid which resembled both parents. This provoked the interest of Cossar Ewart, Professor of Natural History at Edinburgh (1882\u20131927) and a keen geneticist. Ewart crossed a zebra stallion with pony mares to investigate the theory of [[telegony (pregnancy)|telegony]], or paternal impression. In ''[[Origin of Species]]'' (1859), [[Charles Darwin]] mentioned four coloured drawings of hybrids between the ass and zebra. He also wrote\n<blockquote>\nIn Lord Morton's famous hybrid from a chestnut mare and male quagga, the hybrid, and even the pure offspring subsequently produced from the mare by a black Arabian sire, were much more plainly barred across the legs than is even the pure quagga.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Darwin|first1=Charles|title=On the origin of species, 1859.|date=2009|publisher=New York University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0814720585|pages=118\u2013119}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\nIn his book ''[[The Variation of Animals and Plants under Domestication]]'', Darwin described a hybrid ass-zebra specimen in the British Museum as being dappled on its flanks. He also mentioned a \"triple hybrid, from a bay mare, by a hybrid from a male ass and female zebra\" displayed at [[London Zoo]]. This would have required the zebroid sire to be fertile.\n\nDuring the South African War, the [[Boer]]s crossed Chapman's zebras with ponies, to produce animals for transport work, chiefly for hauling guns. A specimen was captured by British forces and presented to [[King Edward VII]] by [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Lord Kitchener]], and was photographed by W. S. Berridge.<ref>''Wonders of Animal Life'', edited by [[John Alexander Hammerton|J. A. Hammerton]] (1930)</ref> Zebras are resistant to sleeping sickness, whereas purebred horses and ponies are not, and  zebra mules hopefully would inherit this resistance.\n\nGrevy's zebra has been crossed with the [[Somali wild ass]] in the early 20th century. [[Zorse]]s were bred by the US government and reported in ''Genetics in Relation to Agriculture'' by E. B. Babcock and R. E. Clausen (early 20th century), in an attempt to investigate inheritance and telegony. The experiments were also reported in ''The Science of Life'' by H G Wells, J Huxley, and G P Wells (around 1929).\n\nInterest in zebra crosses continued in the 1970s. In 1973, a cross between a zebra and a donkey was foaled at the Jerusalem Zoo. They called it a \"hamzab\". In the 1970s, the [[Colchester Zoo]] in England bred zedonks, at first by accident and later to create a disease-resistant riding and draft animal. The experiment was discontinued when zoos became more conservation-minded. A number of hybrids were kept at the zoo after this; the last died in 2009.<ref>{{cite press release| title = Colchester Zoo mourns the loss of Shadow the Zeedonk| url = http://www.colchester-zoo.com/index.cfm?fa=news.press.detail&Press_Release_ID=244| date = 3 April 2009| publisher = Colchester Zoo| url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110708174954/http://www.colchester-zoo.com/index.cfm?fa=news.press.detail&Press_Release_ID=244| archivedate = 8 July 2011| df = dmy-all}}</ref> One adult still remains at the tourist attraction of [[Groombridge Place]]<ref>{{cite web |title=The Enchanted Forest |url=http://www.groombridge.co.uk/enchanted.htm |work=Groombridge Place Gardens |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729084438/http://www.groombridge.co.uk/enchanted.htm |archivedate=29 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> near Tunbridge Wells in Kent.\n\n===21st century===\nToday, various zebroids are bred as riding and draft animals, and as curiosities in circuses and smaller zoos. Zorses are bred in Africa and used for trekking on [[Mount Kenya]];<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-464723/Meet-Eclyse--amazing-zebra-crossing.html|title= Meet Eclyse - the amazing zebra crossing|accessdate= 10 July 2008|work= Mail Online|publisher= Associated Newspapers Ltd|location= London|date= 28 June 2007|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://archive.today/20120729061248/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-464723/Meet-Eclyse--amazing-zebra-crossing.html|archivedate= 29 July 2012|df= dmy-all}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=September 2019}} the zebra parent gives resistance to the [[nagana pest]] disease. A zorse (more accurately a zony) was born at Eden Ostrich World, [[Cumbria]], England, in 2001, after a zebra was left in a field with a Shetland pony. It was referred to as a Zetland. Usually, a zebra stallion is paired with a horse mare or donkey mare, but in 2005, a [[Burchell's zebra]] named Allison produced a zonkey called Alex sired by a donkey at Highland Plantation in the parish of [[Saint Thomas, Barbados]]. Alex, born 21 April 2005, is apparently the first zonkey in Barbados.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Call it zonkey or a deebra? Zebra has a foal sired by a donkey |agency=Associated Press |publisher=NBC News |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/7677651 |date=29 Apr 2005 |accessdate=13 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2007, a stallion, Ulysses, and a zebra mare, Eclipse, produced a hebra named Eclyse, displaying an unusually patchy color coating.<ref>Amanda Billner. [http://www.dn.se/DNet/jsp/polopoly.jsp?d=148&a=665762 \"Zebran \u00e4r en h\u00e4st\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930184652/http://www.dn.se/DNet/jsp/polopoly.jsp?d=148&a=665762 |date=30 September 2007 }} (in Swedish). ''[[Dagens Nyheter]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s webpage, 28 June 2007. Retrieved 30 June 2007.</ref><ref>BBC [http://news.bbc.co.uk/player/nol/newsid_6260000/newsid_6263900/6263928.stm?bw=bb&mp=rm \"Half horse, half zebra - hebra] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904170507/http://news.bbc.co.uk/player/nol/newsid_6260000/newsid_6263900/6263928.stm?bw=bb&mp=rm |date=4 September 2007 }} Retrieved 3 July 2007]</ref> The Wild Animal Safari in [[Springfield, Missouri]], and its sister location in [[Pine Mountain, Harris County, Georgia|Pine Mountain, Georgia]], have several zonkeys as of 31 March 2010.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} In July 2010, a zonkey was born at the Chestatee Wildlife Preserve in Dahlonega, Georgia.<ref>{{cite web | title=Zebra, donkey hybrid born in Dahlonega | url=http://www.gainesvilletimes.com/section/6/article/35810/ | date=27 July 2010 | publisher=Gainesville Times}}</ref> Another zebra\u2013donkey hybrid, like the Barbados zonkey sired by a donkey, was born 3 July 2011 in Haicang Safari Park, [[Haicang Town|Haicang]], [[Xiamen]], China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Donkra: Cross between Donkey, Zebra born |publisher=[[3 News]] |date=5 July 2011 |url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Donkra-Cross-between-Donkey-Zebra-born/tabid/1160/articleID/217643/}}</ref> A zonkey, Ippo, was born 21 July 2013 in an animal reserve, in [[Florence]], [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite news | title=It\u2019s a zonkey! Zebra and donkey hybrid born in Italy | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/zonkey-zebra-donkey-hybrid-born-italy-article-1.1407688 | location=New York | work=Daily News | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727142326/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/zonkey-zebra-donkey-hybrid-born-italy-article-1.1407688 | archivedate=27 July 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Khumba, the offspring of a zebra dam and a dwarf [[Albinism#Other animals|albino]] donkey sire, was born on 21 April 2014 in the zoo of [[Reynosa]] in the state of [[Tamaulipas, Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Zonkey born in a zoo in Mexico |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/centralamericaandthecaribbean/mexico/10787551/Zonkey-born-in-a-zoo-in-Mexico.html |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=25 April 2014 |accessdate=26 April 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426024800/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/centralamericaandthecaribbean/mexico/10787551/Zonkey-born-in-a-zoo-in-Mexico.html |archivedate=26 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> More recently, in November 2018 at a farm in Somerset, a cross between a donkey stallion and a zebra mare was born. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/donkey-zebra-cross-born-uk-britain-somerset-farm-south-barrow-a8617931.html|title=Rare cross between donkey and zebra known as \u2018zonkey\u2019 born on Somerset farm|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-11-06|language=en-GB}}</ref> The male foal was described as a zonkey by its owner and has been named Zippy.\n\n==Popular culture==\nZorses have appeared in several TV shows and movies. In the ''[[Viva La Bam]]'' episode \"Groundhog Day\". in the final race, [[Brandon Dicamillo]]'s sled is a zorse. It was colored pink, blue, purple. and red. On the 'uncommentary' on the DVD seasons of ''Viva La Bam'', Tim Glomb says, \"If you send me a list of all the episodes where the zorse is, I'll give you a dollar\". The 2007 movie ''[[I'm Reed Fish]]'' features a zorse named Zabrina. In the movie ''[[Racing Stripes]]'', an animated zorse appears in the alternate ending. He is the son of Stripes, a zebra [[stallion]] and Sandy, a grey Arabian mare.\n\nZorses have also appeared in books. They are briefly mentioned several times in [[George R.R. Martin]]'s ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' series of fantasy novels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awoiaf.westeros.org/index.php/Zorse|title=Zorse|website=westeros.org|accessdate=6 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20160313033540/http://awoiaf.westeros.org/index.php/Zorse|archivedate=13 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sutton Coleman wrote a sonnet about zorses and published it in his 2007 book, ''[[Ligers]], [[Tigons]], and Zorses, Oh My!'' In [[Roald Dahl]]'s book ''[[Going Solo]]'',  several other characters and he speculate on how nice it would be to own a zorse, although they admit it would be difficult to [[domestication of animals|train]].\n\nThe fantasy setting ''[[Glorantha]]'' has a magical fertile breed of horses crossed with zebras based on the city of Pavis. This small population is extended by breeding stallions of these breeds with ordinary horses, creating an infertile breed called Cavalry Zebras.\n \nThe video game ''[[Red Dead Redemption]]'' has the \"Zebra Donkey\" available as a multiplayer mount.\n\nIn ''[[El Tigre: The Adventures of Manny Rivera]]'', the characters' school's mascot is the famed Zebra Donkey.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Zorses}}\n*[http://www.messybeast.com/genetics/hybrid-equines.htm Hybrid Equines] Information and images of different zebroids\n*[http://photos1.blogger.com/x/blogger2/6012/701/600/z/85488/gse_multipart23028.jpg Eclyse] - Photo of a zebroid named Eclyse\n*{{cite news |title=Zenkey foal a hybrid star |date=29 Aug 2003 |work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/08/28/1062050609625.html }}\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/1408717.stm BBC News (26 June 2001): \"Zebra Hybrid is Cute Surprise\"]\n*[http://www.metro.co.uk/weird/article.html?in_article_id=54968 Metro (28 June 2007): \"A single-zorsed story\"]\n*Dorsett, Katherine. \"[http://www.cnn.com/2010/US/09/23/what.is.zedonk/index.html What the heck is a zedonk?]\" ''[[CNN]]''. 23 September 2010.\n*[http://www.izzza.com The International Zebra Zorse Zonkey Association ]\n*[http://www.educatedearth.net/video.php?id=3559 Video of a Zorse]\n*[http://www.ansa.it/web/notizie/rubriche/english/2013/07/22/Rare-zebra-donkey-mix-born-Florence-animal-reserve_9059572.html Rare zebra-donkey mix born in Florence animal reserve: The zonkey named Ippo only one in Italy]\n\n{{Mammal hybrids|state=collapsed}}\n{{equine|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Equid hybrids]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix PMC warnings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zebroid"}
{"title_page": "Walking with Beasts", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Walking With Prehistoric Beasts\n| image = BBCWWB large.jpg\n| caption = The original DVD cover of ''Walking With Prehistoric Beasts''\n| show_name_2 = ''Walking with Prehistoric Beasts''\n| genre = [[Television documentary|Documentary]]\n| creator = [[Tim Haines]]<br />[[Jasper James]]<br />Andrew Wilks\n| developer = Andrew Wilks\n| writer = Kate Bartlett<br />Jasper James<br />Michael Olmert<br />Nigel Paterson\n| director = Jasper James<br />Nigel Paterson\n| creative_director = Mike Milne\n| narrated = [[Kenneth Branagh]] (UK)<br />[[Stockard Channing]] (US)<br />[[Christian Slater]] ([[Prehistoric Planet]])\n| composer = [[Ben Bartlett]]\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| num_episodes = 6\n| list_episodes = \n| executive_producer = [[Tim Haines]]\n| producer = Jasper James<br />Nigel Paterson\n| location = [[Arizona]], [[Brazil]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Florida]], [[Java]], [[Mexico]], [[South Africa]], [[Yukon]]\n| cinematography = John Howarth<br />Michael Pitts\n| editor = Greg Smith<br />Andrew Wilks\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| company = [[BBC Natural History Unit]]<br />[[Impossible Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[BBC Worldwide]]\n| first_aired = {{start date|df=yes|2001|11|15}}\n| last_aired = {{end date|df=yes|2001|12|21}}\n| preceded_by = ''[[Walking with Dinosaurs]]''\n| followed_by = ''[[Walking with Monsters]]''\n| related = Other shows in the ''[[Walking with...]]'' series\n| website = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00tbkjh\n| production_website = \n| num_series = <!-- 1 unnecessary for miniseries-->\n| channel = [[BBC One]]\n}}\n\n'''''Walking with Beasts''''' ('''''Walking with Prehistoric Beasts''''' in North American releases) is a 2001 six-part [[television]] [[documentary]] [[miniseries]], produced by the [[BBC Natural History Unit]]. It is the second installment of the [[Walking With...]] series and a sequel to ''[[Walking with Dinosaurs]]''. ''Beasts'' takes place after the [[extinction of the non-avian dinosaurs]] 65 million years ago depicted in ''Walking with Dinosaurs'', and recreates animals of the [[Cenozoic]] with [[computer-generated imagery]] and [[animatronics]]. Like ''Dinosaurs'', its narrative is presented in the style of a traditional [[nature documentary]]. Some of the concepts it illustrates are the [[Cetacean evolution|evolution of whales]], [[Evolution of the horse|horses]], [[elephants]] and [[Human evolution|humans]].\n\nIn North America, ''Beasts'' was broadcast on the [[Discovery Channel]] with [[Stockard Channing]] replacing [[Kenneth Branagh]] as the narrator. It would later be re-edited and re-narrated for the second season of ''[[Prehistoric Planet]]'' for the [[Discovery Kids]] lineup, with [[Christian Slater]] providing the narration instead of [[Kenneth Branagh]].\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Walk With Beasts exhibition.jpg|thumb|left|Puppet heads used in the series, [[Horniman Museum]], London]] \nProducer [[Tim Haines]] wanted to create a sequel to ''Walking with Dinosaurs'' so the general public could discover the fascinating mammals of the Cenozoic, which were less represented in popular culture [[Dinosaurs in popular culture|than dinosaurs]].<ref>{{cite video|title=Tim Haines Production Interview|medium=DVD featurette|people=Tim Haines|date=2002|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nAs with ''Walking with Dinosaurs'', the film crews would go to locations that matched the depicted time periods fairly closely and shoot either empty landscapes (when the animals would be created later with CGI) or [[animatronic]] animals for close-ups. Sometimes it was necessary to replicate the impact the animated animals would have on their environment\u2014such as footprints left in the snow by a woolly mammoth.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Of - TV Production|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011223144053/http://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/prod/index.shtml|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/prod/|date=2001|archivedate=2001-12-23|publisher=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The animatronics' broad movements were controlled by puppeteers, while their more subtle movements were remote-controlled and operated via [[servo motor]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Of - Animatronics|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011221070809/http://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/anim/|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/anim/|date=2001|archivedate=2001-12-21|publisher=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe [[visual effects]] budget was around 7 or 8 million dollars, much lower than a feature film of the time. Tim Haines attributed this to solid planning.<ref>{{cite video|title=Tim Haines Production Interview|medium=DVD featurette|people=Tim Haines|date=2002|publisher=BBC|quote=The budget for this was between seven and eight million, but in terms of what we were trying to do, that is bargain basement. To give you some idea, when you see films like ''Jurassic Park'' ... they have effects budgets that run into many tens of millions of pounds. They have to, that's what they're selling. Seven to eight million for what is massively more effects shots and effects material is very, very cheap. But that's because we know exactly what we're doing and what we want from those effects and we're very targeted in our approach. We don't waste any effects at all.}}</ref> The [[fur]] coats and moving parts of mammals made the creatures in ''Beasts'' more challenging to animate than the scaly reptiles of ''Walking with Dinosaurs''.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011221074333/http://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/cg/index.shtml|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/cg/index.shtml|publisher=bbc.co.uk|date=2001|archivedate=2001-12-21|title=Making Of - Computer Graphics}}</ref> Short fur was animated with tricks, and long shaggy coats (like the [[woolly mammoth]]'s) with fur [[shader]]s.\n\nLive actors were used for the [[anatomically modern human]]s and Neanderthals in \"Mammoth Journey\".<ref>{{cite video|title=\"The Beasts Within\"|medium=DVD featurette|publisher=BBC|date=2002}}</ref> In \"Next of Kin\", extreme close-ups of ''Australopithecus'' also employed actors wearing prosthetics.<ref>{{cite video|title=Production Interviews|medium=DVD featurette|people=Tim Haines|date=2002|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n\"Sabre Tooth\" was shot in Brazil, where ''Smilodon'' actually roamed.<ref>{{cite web|date=2001|archivedate=2001-12-14|title= Making Of - Model Making|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011214114548/http://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/models/index.shtml|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/models/index.shtml|publisher=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Filming of the [[Last glacial period|ice age]] landscapes for the final episode took place in Canada's [[Yukon Territory]].\n\n==List of episodes==\n===''Walking with Beasts''===\n[[BBC One]] aired the series weekly on Thursday nights, with a regular of repeats the following Sunday afternoon. In 2010, the series was repeated on [[BBC Three]] in [[Omnibus (broadcast)|omnibus]] format, as three hour-long episodes.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00sndkw Walking with Beasts -  Compilations - Episode 1] ''bbc.co.uk.'' Web. Retrieved 19 September 2018.</ref>\n\n<div style=\"width:75%;\">\n{{Episode table |background=#2155B0 |overall= |title= |aux1= |director= |airdate= |viewers= |country=U.K. |aux1T=Time |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 1\n| Title= New Dawn\n| RTitle= <ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0095rlk Walking with Beasts -  New Dawn] ''bbc.co.uk.'' Web. Retrieved 19 September 2018.</ref>\n| Aux1= 49 mya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|15|df=y}}\n| Viewers= 13.99<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/weekly-top-30/|title=Weekly top 30 programmes|publisher=BARB|access-date= 19 September 2018}}</ref><ref group=note>7 day data, including the original Thursday broadcast and Sunday repeat for the six main episodes.</ref>\n| ShortSummary=:'''49 million years ago, Early Eocene (Germany)'''\n:Filming location: [[Java]]\n[[File:Gastornis Walking With Beasts.jpg|thumb|''[[Gastornis]]'' as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']]\nThe episode starts by showing how the dinosaurs were dominating the land and that mammals were small. Then it shows how [[Chicxulub impactor|\"an asteroid the size of Mount Everest\"]] struck the Earth and [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event|demolished the dinosaurs]], and how mammals evolved into new forms thereafter.  The first episode depicts the warm tropical world of the early [[Eocene]], sixteen million years after the [[extinction]] of the non-avian dinosaurs. Birds, the surviving lineage of the dinosaurs, including the giant carnivorous ''[[Gastornis]]'', rule this world, while mammals are still very small. The setting is near the [[Messel pit]] in [[Germany]]. Due to volcanic activity, sudden bulk escapes of [[carbon dioxide]] trapped underneath lakes pose a significant hazard to the local wildlife. The episode centers around a ''[[Leptictidium]]'' family, a leaping, shrew-like mammal, which has emerged in the dawn hours to forage for food. As the mother ''Leptictidium'' forages, first in solidarity, and then with her pups, she wanders near a large predatory mammal, identified as an ''[[Ambulocetus]]'', a \"walking whale\". Despite its crocodilian similarity, the ''Ambulocetus'' is shown swimming by [[Evolution of cetaceans|caudal undulation]] like a modern cetacean.\nA female ''Gastornis'', who has been taking care of the single egg in her nest, makes two attempts to hunt a small herd of ''[[Eurohippus|Propalaeotherium]]'', early horses. The first attempt fails when sounds among the vegetation betray her presence. The second attack proves successful when the ''Propalaeotherium'' consume fermenting grapes and are unable to evade her attack. The ''Gastornis'' also defends her territory from another ''Gastornis''. Unfortunately, while the mother hunts, a horde of ''[[Titanomyrma]]'', giant carnivorous [[ants]], encounter the egg when it was just starting to hatch, and successfully kill and eat the chick. When the female discovers her dead offspring at dusk she leaves the forest to try and start another family.\n\nWith the arrival of night, a band of lemur-like ''[[Godinotia]]'', socialize and copulate in the dark. ''Ambulocetus'' finally manages to catch a [[Creodonta|creodont]] near the lake edge. As the night wears on, an earth tremor unleashes trapped carbon dioxide out from underneath the lake and the gas suffocates most of the surrounding life. The ''Leptictidium'' survive because the nest was upwind of the gas, and ''Gastornis'' also survived because she left that area in the forest.\n\nIt is mentioned that although the ''Leptictidium'' survived the gas, they would ultimately leave no descendants, while the ''Ambulocetus'', who was killed by the lethal gases, would evolve into the whales, hereby setting the scene for the next episode.\n\n'''Animals:'''\n''[[Leptictidium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Gastornis]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Ambulocetus]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Eurohippus|Propalaeotherium]]'' <ref group=note>Specimen featured in episode was based on ''Propaleotherium parvulum'' which is now considered to be synonymous with ''Eurohippus''</ref>\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Godinotia]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Eurotamandua]]'' (unnamed, live-acted by a [[tamandua]])\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Titanomyrma]]'' (unnamed, identified as giant ants)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Lesmesodon]]'' (unnamed)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Asiatosuchus]]'' (live-acted by a [[crocodile]])\n{{\u00b7}}[[Gecko]]\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Tyrannosaurus]]'' (stock footage from ''[[Walking with Dinosaurs]]'')\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Ankylosaurus]]'' (stock footage from ''[[Walking with Dinosaurs]]'')\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Didelphodon]]'' (stock footage from ''[[Walking with Dinosaurs]]'')\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 2\n| Title= Whale Killer\n| Aux1= 36 mya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|22|df=y}}\n| Viewers= 11.34\n| ShortSummary= :'''36 million years ago, Late Eocene (Pakistan/Tethys Sea)'''\n:Filming location: [[Florida]]\n[[File:Andrewsarchus head model.jpg|thumb|''[[Andrewsarchus]]'' as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']]\nThe second episode is set in late [[Eocene]], when the [[polar caps]] froze over and drastically changed the Earth's [[ocean currents]] and [[climate]]. The first part of the episode explains how an early [[whale]], ''[[Basilosaurus]]'' mates and how the world is changing into an ocean [[famine]]. On land there is an ''[[Andrewsarchus]]'' driven to the beach to feed on [[sea turtle]]s. The narrator explains that ''Andrewsarchus'', the largest land mammal [[predator]] ever to walk the earth, has hooves and is related to sheep, so it is, in a sense, a \"sheep in wolf's clothing\". Back in the ocean, a starving mother ''Basilosaurus'' is forced to hunt in the [[mangrove]] swamps of [[Africa]], which will later become the [[Sahara Desert]]. Unable to catch a primate called ''[[Apidium]]'' due to a [[Physogaleus|shark]] killing one of the primates and spooking the others, she is then hunting a lone ''[[Moeritherium]]''. The ''Moeritherium'' crawls on to land, but in the mangroves, land does not last long. However the ''Moeritherium'' escapes and the ''Basilosaurus'' returns to the sea. The cast moves on to land where a herd of ''[[Embolotherium]]'' struggle to survive: one of their calves dies after birth and two ''Andrewsarchus'' feast on it, but the mother ''Embolotherium'' drives them away because she has a strong bond with her offspring, even if it is dead. Back in the sea, the mother ''Basilosaurus'' preys on a group of [[Dolphin]]-like ''[[Dorudon]]'' and their young, and is successful. The episode ends with the mother ''Basilosaurus'' swimming with her newborn calf.\n\nIt is acknowledged in the end that soon Africa will be pulled closer to Europe, causing the [[Tethys Sea]] to disappear. While whales as a whole will survive [[Eocene-Oligocene extinction event|the ensuing extinction]], ''Basilosaurus'', unfortunately, will disappear with the Tethys as well.\n\n'''Animals:'''\n''[[Basilosaurus]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Andrewsarchus]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Embolotherium]]'' (identified as brontothere)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Dorudon]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Moeritherium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Apidium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Physogaleus]]'' (identified as shark)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Puppigerus]]'' (identified as turtle)\n{{\u00b7}}[[Vulture]]\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 3\n| Title= Land of Giants\n| Aux1= 25  mya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|29|df=y}}\n| Viewers= 9.27\n| ShortSummary= :'''25 million years ago, Late Oligocene (Mongolia)'''\n:Filming location: [[Mexico]], [[Arizona]]\n[[File:Entelodon Walking With Beasts.jpg|thumb|''[[Entelodon]]'' as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']]\nThe third episode takes place during the late [[Oligocene]], in [[Mongolia]], where there were seasonal [[Rain|rains]] followed by a long [[drought]]. It focuses on a mother ''[[Paraceratherium]]'', a massive hornless [[rhinoceros]], the largest land mammal to ever live as one night, she gives birth to a healthy male calf, while trying to fend off the predatory ''[[Hyaenodon]]''. By morning, the calf slowly learns how to walk and after a week, his mother takes him out to the open plain where he will spend the rest of his life. The inquisitive calf runs into a mother ''[[Cynodictis]]'', who drives him out of her family burrow to protect her pups. The calf then learns to survive on his own, by copying his mother's actions. Not long after, his mother's previous calf arrives, but the mother violently repels him. A ''Hyaenodon'' is then seen stalking a herd of ''[[Chalicotherium]]'', successfully killing one, but a trio of ''[[Entelodon]]'' drive it off the carcass. During the dry season, there is a huge shortage of food and water, putting even the hardiest to their greatest stress. The mother, now dehydrated, has not been able to produce enough milk for the calf, who's getting weaker and weaker as time progresses. At night, the pair are joined by an older female, who leads them to a small, muddy lake, where they drink their fill and gain back their strength. The wet season returns, the water levels rise, flooding the ''Cynodictis'' family burrow, and drowning the sleeping pups. The mother and calf have to cross a river, the mother making it with ease, while the calf struggled to make it up a muddy bank, but he finally succeeded. 3 years pass, and the calf is furiously chased away by his mother. He then was not seen for days, but when he was seen, he was limping and had a leg injury, possibly caused by another young male ''Paraceratherium''. When he returned to his mother, she aggressively chased him away, as she now has a new calf to nurture. After 3 months, the calf learns how to stand on his own two feet and successfully drives away an ''Entelodon''.\n\n'''Animals:'''\n''[[Paraceratherium]]'' (identified as indricothere)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Hyaenodon]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Entelodon]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Chalicotherium]]'' (identified as chalicothere)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Cynodictis]]'' (identified as bear-dog)<ref>{{cite book\n | last = Haines\n | first = Tim\n | authorlink = Tim Haines\n | title = The Complete Guide to Prehistoric Life\n | url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781554071258\n | url-access = registration\n | publisher = Firefly Books\n | location = Canada\n | date = 2006\n | page = [https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781554071258/page/176 176]\n | isbn = 1-55407-125-9}}\n</ref>\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 4\n| Title= Next of Kin\n| Aux1= 3.2  mya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|12|6|df=y}}\n| Viewers= - <ref group=note>This episode did not reach the Top 30 programmes.</ref>\n| ShortSummary= :'''3.2 million years ago, Late Pliocene (Ethiopia)'''\n:Filming location: [[South Africa]], [[Ethiopia]]\n[[File:Walk With Beasts exhibition Ancylotherium model.jpg|thumb|''[[Ancylotherium]]'' as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']] \nThe fourth episode takes place in the [[Great Rift Valley, Ethiopia|Great Rift Valley]] in northeastern [[Africa]] of the late [[Pliocene]]. The climate has changed, and now great grasslands have replaced trees, with many modern-day animals appearing with them. The episode focuses around a tribe of small [[hominid]]s known as ''[[Australopithecus]]'', one of the first [[ape]]s able to walk upright and a close ancestor to [[humans]]. The ''Australopithecus'' has evolved to walk upright so as to better manoeuvre the plains as well as the climb the trees. However, it notes that although the ''Australopithecus'' looks human, it still only has a brain the size of a [[Common chimpanzee|chimpanzee]]'s. Some of the topics explored in the episode are the close social bonds among the [[tribe]], how they use [[Social grooming|grooming]] as a means of [[communication]], and how they work together to forage for food and to defend one another from attacks from such animals as an angry male ''[[Deinotherium]]'', an ancestor of the modern [[elephant]] which they have to run from to avoid being crushed, and the [[Felidae|feline]] predator ''[[Dinofelis]]''. It touches upon how competing tribes of ''Australopithecus'' war among one another, although most of the fighting is for show. It also explains the [[hierarchy]] in the tribe among the males, who are much larger than the females, and tells a story of how the dominating male nicknamed Grey is eventually overcome by another male nicknamed Hercules, who wins the right to feed first at a carrion and to mate with the females. The main story tells of a young ''Australopithecus'' nicknamed Blue whose mother has been killed by malaria. He and his tribe are later forced to flee their homeland during a fight over a waterhole with a rival tribe. After a long journey in search of a new home, Blue fits into his tribe by rallying them into scaring off a hungry ''Dinofelis''.\n\n'''Animals:'''\n''[[Australopithecus]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Dinofelis]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Deinotherium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Ancylotherium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}[[Common warthog]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[White rhinoceros]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Black-backed jackal]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[White-backed vulture]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Zebra]] (carcass)\n{{\u00b7}}[[Ostrich]] (egg)\n\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 5\n| Title= Sabre Tooth\n| Aux1= 1 mya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|12|13|df=y}}\n| Viewers= 5.87\n| ShortSummary= :'''1 million years ago, Early Pleistocene (Paraguay)'''\n:Filming location: [[Brazil]]\n[[File:Phorusrhacos - Walk With Beasts.jpg|thumb|''[[Phorusrhacos]]'' as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']]\nThe fifth episode shows the strange [[fauna]] of the isolated continent of [[South America]] and explores the effects of the [[Great American Interchange]], which had happened 1.5 million years earlier. Since South America had drifted apart from [[Antarctica]] 30 million years ago, many unique [[mammals]] had evolved, including the ''[[Doedicurus]]'', an armoured [[armadillo]]-like mammal with a cannon ball-sized spiked club on its tail; the ''[[Macrauchenia]],'' a [[camel]]-like mammal with a long trunk; and the ''[[Megatherium]]'', a giant [[ground sloth]]. Before the continents of South America and [[North America]] collided, a 10-foot-tall predatory [[Phorusrhacidae|terror bird]] called ''[[Phorusrhacos]]'', had reigned as [[top predator]]. However, the great cats migrating from the north, soon displaced them as top predators. The episode focuses on a male ''[[Smilodon]],'' a [[sabre-toothed cat]], called Half Tooth, whose leadership of a [[pride]] is threatened by two rival males who are brothers and work together against him. Half Tooth wisely backs off without any serious injuries, feeling that the rival males would be too strong for him. The rival males kill Half Tooth's cubs, and take over his pride. Next, the episode shows the ''Smilodon'' hunting down ''Macrauchenia'' and trying to protect the remaining two young from the two males. In the background, ''Phorusrhacos'' wait to scavenge the ''Macrauchenia'', which the pride of ''Smilodon''  have killed. However, a ''Megatherium'' charges the ''Smilodon'', in order to eat some of the carrion as a diet supplement. In the process, the ''Megatherium'' kills the dominant rival male, enabling Half Tooth to return, kill the other male and reclaim his territory. A year later, his mate has another litter of cubs.\n\n'''Animals:'''\n''[[Smilodon]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Phorusrhacos]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Macrauchenia]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Megatherium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Doedicurus]]''\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 6\n| Title= Mammoth Journey\n| Aux1=  30,000 ya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|12|20|df=y}}\n| Viewers= 9.48\n| ShortSummary= :'''30,000 years ago, Late Pleistocene (Belgium)'''\n:Filming location: [[Yukon]]\n[[File:Woolly Rhinoceros Hunt.jpg|thumb|[[Woolly rhinoceros]] as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']]\nThe sixth episode takes place during the last [[Ice Age]] of the late [[Pleistocene]]. It starts in the peak of the summer. The [[North Sea]] has become a [[Doggerland|grassy plain]] because the ice at the polar caps has caused the [[sea level]]s to drop significantly. Grazing on the plain are herds of [[woolly mammoth]]s, [[saiga antelope]]s, and [[bison]]. A clan of [[Cro-Magnon]] is also there spending the summer. The central focus of the episode is the migration of the herd of mammoths as they travel 400 kilometres from the North Sea to the [[Swiss Alps]] for the winter and then back again in the spring. As the mammoth herd migrates south, the episode shows two large [[deer]], the [[elk]]-like ''[[Irish elk|Megaloceros]]'', fighting for rights to a [[harem]] of females. As the male elk fight, a group of Cro-Magnons ambushes them and kills one. A mother mammoth and her baby are separated from the herd, but survive an encounter with a [[Panthera leo spelaea|European cave lion]]. When the herd of mammoths reaches the Swiss Alps, the mother and baby mammoth reunite with their herd. The episode also depicts a clan of [[Neanderthal]]s, who have especially evolved to survive in the cold climate. One is charged by a [[woolly rhinoceros]], but escapes, in part because of his stocky constitution. The climax of the episode is when the clan of Neanderthals attack the herd of mammoth as they turn back to the north. The Neanderthals are gifted hunters who are able to chase two mammoths off a cliff by using [[fire]] and spears, one of them being the matriarch of the herd. The episode ends in the [[Oxford University Museum of Natural History]] with people looking at various [[skeleton]]s of some descendants of the animals featured in the series. The camera then pulls back through the roof of the [[museum]] until the whole world is visible. The narrator states that, \"We have since built museums to celebrate the past, and spent decades studying prehistoric lives. And if all this has taught us anything, it is this: no species lasts forever.\"\n\n'''Animals:'''\n[[Woolly Mammoth]] \n{{\u00b7}}''[[Irish elk|Megaloceros]]''\n{{\u00b7}}[[Woolly Rhinoceros]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Cro-Magnon]] (identified as humans)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Panthera spelaea]]'' (identified as cave lion)\n{{\u00b7}}[[Neanderthal]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Saiga antelope]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Wolf]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Wisent]]\n\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}\n}}\n</div>\n\n===''The Science of Walking with Beasts''===\nA two-episode companion documentary, ''The Science of Walking with Beasts'', aired in November 2001 on [[BBC One]]. This series featured interviews with palaeontologists and explanations of how the fossil record and modern day descendants have informed what is known about the animals depicted in ''Beasts'', as well as brief sections showing the development of the CGI and animatronic animals used in the series.\n\n{{Episode table |background=FFFF00 |overall= |title= |director= |airdate= |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 1\n| Title= Triumph of the Beasts\n| DirectedBy=Kate Bartlett\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|21|df=y}}\n| ShortSummary= An explanation of how mammals evolved to be larger and more prevalent, eventually taking the dinosaurs' place as some of the most successful creatures on the planet. The [[Messel pit]] fossil site and fossil discoveries of [[Roy Chapman Andrews]] are featured.\n|LineColor = FFFF00 \n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 2\n| Title= The Beasts Within\n| DirectedBy=Nigel Paterson \n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|28|df=y}}\n| ShortSummary= An explanation of how prehistoric apes evolved into modern man, and which attributes made human ancestors so successful. The [[La Cotte de St Brelade]] site is featured.\n}}\n}}\n\n==Release==\n''Walking with Beasts'' was originally broadcast in the United Kingdom on the [[BBC1]] from 12 November to 21 December 2001. In North America, it aired on December 9, 2001 on the [[Discovery Channel]]. The UK broadcast was the first non-sports BBC interactive programme.<ref>{{cite news|title=Digital Evolution for BBC Beasts|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/oct/09/newmedia.broadcasting|newspaper=The Guardian|last=Gibson|first=Owen|date=2001-10-09}}</ref>\n''Beasts'' was released on [[VHS]] on 26 November 2001. A DVD release came the next year on 12 February for North America (as ''Walking with Prehistoric Beasts'') and 8 April in the United Kingdom. The North American release restores the original narration by Kenneth Branagh. The DVD contains several special features: two 50-minute documentaries on prehistoric life, \"Triumph of the Beasts\" (about Cenozoic life at large) and \"The Beasts Within\" (which focuses on the humans and primates in the show); interviews with Tim Haines; animated storyboards; a photo gallery; and several fact files on the animals featured in the series. This edition was bundled with ''The Complete Walking with... Collection'' which came out on 23 July 2002.\n\nA re-edited and re-narrated version of ''Beasts'' was presented as the second season of ''[[Prehistoric Planet]]'', a [[Discovery Kids]] programme intended for a younger audience than ''Walking with...''\n\n===Promotion===\n''Beasts'' was promoted with a breakfast cereal tie-in from Kellogg's and the video game ''Walking with Beasts: Operation Salvage'' for Windows PCs.<ref>{{cite web|title=65 Million Years of Strategy|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/10/05/65-million-years-of-strategy|website=IGN|date=2001-10-05}}</ref> The soundtrack by [[Ben Bartlett]] was released on [[CD]]. An exhibition took place at the [[Herbert Art Gallery and Museum]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Winner of competition for Walking with Beasts exhibition at Coventry's The Herbert|newspaper=Coventry Telegraph|date=2001-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe first episode of ''Walking with Beasts'' attracted an audience of 8.5 million, 35 per cent of television viewers at that time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Munching with Beasts|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/2743440/Munching-with-Beasts.html|date=2001-11-27|last=Mills|first=Dominic|newspaper=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nCritics generally enjoyed ''Walking with Beasts''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-481264.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911161220/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-481264.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-09-11|title=Walking with Prehistoric Beasts|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=2001-12-09|last=Zad|first=Martie}}{{Subscription|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> However, there were some complaints about overbearing narration and disappointing visual effects.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/16/firstnight.broadcasting|title=First night: walking with beasts|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===Companion book===\nA companion book was written by [[Tim Haines]] to accompany the first screening of the series in 2001. As with ''Walking with Dinosaurs'', the written version of ''Walking with Beasts'' elaborated on the background for each story, went further in explaining the science on which much of the programme as based, and included descriptions of several animals not identified or featured in the series.<ref>{{cite book|last=Haines|first=Tim|title=Walking with Beasts: A Prehistoric Safari|publisher=DK Publishing|date=2001|ISBN=0789478293|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/walkingwithbeast00hain}}</ref>\n\n==Scientific accuracy==\nIn the first episode, the ''[[Gastornis]]'' are depicted as carnivorous predators, which is in agreement with their perception at the time as \"terror birds.\" However, in 2013, a scientific study suggested that the bird was probably omnivorous or a herbivore.<ref>{{cite web|last=Viegas|first=Jennifer|url=http://www.abc.net.au/science/articles/2013/08/30/3837440.htm?site=science/talkingscience&topic=ancient|title='Terror bird' was scary-looking vegetarian|publisher=''ABC Science''|date=August 30, 2013|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Ambulocetus]]'' is depicted as amphibious; later studies suggest that it was fully aquatic.<ref name=\"aquatic2016\">{{cite journal | first1 = K. | last1 = Ando | first2 = S.-I. | last2 = Fujiwara | title = Farewell to life on land \u2013 thoracic strength as a new indicator to determine paleoecology in secondary aquatic mammals | doi = 10.1111/joa.12518 | journal = Journal of Anatomy | volume = 229 | issue = 6 | date = 2016 | pages = 768\u2013777}}</ref> ''Ambulocetus'' lived in Pakistan, not Germany.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Paleotology database|url=https://paleobiodb.org/classic/basicCollectionSearch?a=basicCollectionSearch&collection_no=49002|title=H-GSP 9210 (Eocene of Pakistan)}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nThe series won an [[Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program (for Programming One Hour or More)|Outstanding Animated Program]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sn/prehistoric_life/tv_radio/wwbeasts/ Walking with Beasts - BBC Science & Nature]''\n*{{IMDb title|0286285|title=Walking with Prehistoric Beasts}}\n*''[https://web.archive.org/web/20050527095948/http://www.abc.net.au/beasts/ Walking with Beasts]'' at [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]\n\n{{Walking with}}\n{{EmmyAward AnimationLessThanHour 2001\u20132025}}\n{{Impossible Pictures}}\n{{BBC Natural History Unit}}\n\n[[Category:2001 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2001 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000s British television series]]\n[[Category:BBC television documentaries]]\n[[Category:Discovery Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about prehistoric life]]\n[[Category:Television series about mammals]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program winners]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (television series)]]\n[[Category:Walking with...]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Walking With Prehistoric Beasts\n| image = BBCWWB large.jpg\n| caption = The original DVD cover of ''Walking With Prehistoric Beasts''\n| show_name_2 = ''Walking with Prehistoric Beasts''\n| genre = [[Television documentary|Documentary]]\n| creator = [[Tim Haines]]<br />[[Jasper James]]<br />Andrew Wilks\n| developer = Andrew Wilks\n| writer = Kate Bartlett<br />Jasper James<br />Michael Olmert<br />Nigel Paterson\n| director = Jasper James<br />Nigel Paterson\n| creative_director = Mike Milne\n| narrated = [[Kenneth Branagh]] (UK)<br />[[Stockard Channing]] (US)<br />[[Christian Slater]] ([[Prehistoric Planet]])\n| composer = [[Ben Bartlett]]\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| num_episodes = 6\n| list_episodes = \n| executive_producer = [[Tim Haines]]\n| producer = Jasper James<br />Nigel Paterson\n| location = [[Arizona]], [[Brazil]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Florida]], [[Java]], [[Mexico]], [[South Africa]], [[Yukon]]\n| cinematography = John Howarth<br />Michael Pitts\n| editor = Greg Smith<br />Andrew Wilks\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| company = [[BBC Natural History Unit]]<br />[[Impossible Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[BBC Worldwide]]\n| first_aired = {{start date|df=yes|2001|11|15}}\n| last_aired = {{end date|df=yes|2001|12|21}}\n| preceded_by = ''[[Walking with Dinosaurs]]''\n| followed_by = ''[[Walking with Monsters]]''\n| related = Other shows in the ''[[Walking with...]]'' series\n| website = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00tbkjh\n| production_website = \n| num_series = <!-- 1 unnecessary for miniseries-->\n| channel = [[BBC One]]\n}}\n\n'''''Walking with Beasts''''' ('''''Walking with Prehistoric Beasts''''' in North American releases) is a 2001 six-part [[television]] [[documentary]] [[miniseries]], produced by the [[BBC Natural History Unit]]. It is the second installment of the [[Walking With...]] series and a sequel to ''[[Walking with Dinosaurs]]''. ''Beasts'' takes place after the [[extinction of the non-avian dinosaurs]] 65 million years ago depicted in ''Walking with Dinosaurs'', and recreates animals of the [[Cenozoic]] with [[computer-generated imagery]] and [[animatronics]]. Like ''Dinosaurs'', its narrative is presented in the style of a traditional [[nature documentary]]. Some of the concepts it illustrates are the [[Cetacean evolution|evolution of whales]], [[Evolution of the horse|horses]], [[elephants]] and [[Human evolution|humans]].\n\nIn North America, ''Beasts'' was broadcast on the [[Discovery Channel]] with [[Stockard Channing]] replacing [[Kenneth Branagh]] as the narrator. It would later be re-edited and re-narrated for the second season of ''[[Prehistoric Planet]]'' for the [[Discovery Kids]] lineup, with [[Christian Slater]] providing the narration instead of [[Kenneth Branagh]].\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Walk With Beasts exhibition.jpg|thumb|left|Puppet heads used in the series, [[Horniman Museum]], London]] \nProducer [[Tim Haines]] wanted to create a sequel to ''Walking with Dinosaurs'' so the general public could discover the fascinating mammals of the Cenozoic, which were less represented in popular culture [[Dinosaurs in popular culture|than dinosaurs]].<ref>{{cite video|title=Tim Haines Production Interview|medium=DVD featurette|people=Tim Haines|date=2002|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nAs with ''Walking with Dinosaurs'', the film crews would go to locations that matched the depicted time periods fairly closely and shoot either empty landscapes (when the animals would be created later with CGI) or [[animatronic]] animals for close-ups. Sometimes it was necessary to replicate the impact the animated animals would have on their environment\u2014such as footprints left in the snow by a woolly mammoth.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Of - TV Production|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011223144053/http://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/prod/index.shtml|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/prod/|date=2001|archivedate=2001-12-23|publisher=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The animatronics' broad movements were controlled by puppeteers, while their more subtle movements were remote-controlled and operated via [[servo motor]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Of - Animatronics|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011221070809/http://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/anim/|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/anim/|date=2001|archivedate=2001-12-21|publisher=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe [[visual effects]] budget was around 7 or 8 million dollars, much lower than a feature film of the time. Tim Haines attributed this to solid planning.<ref>{{cite video|title=Tim Haines Production Interview|medium=DVD featurette|people=Tim Haines|date=2002|publisher=BBC|quote=The budget for this was between seven and eight million, but in terms of what we were trying to do, that is bargain basement. To give you some idea, when you see films like ''Jurassic Park'' ... they have effects budgets that run into many tens of millions of pounds. They have to, that's what they're selling. Seven to eight million for what is massively more effects shots and effects material is very, very cheap. But that's because we know exactly what we're doing and what we want from those effects and we're very targeted in our approach. We don't waste any effects at all.}}</ref> The [[fur]] coats and moving parts of mammals made the creatures in ''Beasts'' more challenging to animate than the scaly reptiles of ''Walking with Dinosaurs''.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011221074333/http://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/cg/index.shtml|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/cg/index.shtml|publisher=bbc.co.uk|date=2001|archivedate=2001-12-21|title=Making Of - Computer Graphics}}</ref> Short fur was animated with tricks, and long shaggy coats (like the [[woolly mammoth]]'s) with fur [[shader]]s.\n\nLive actors were used for the [[anatomically modern human]]s and Neanderthals in \"Mammoth Journey\".<ref>{{cite video|title=\"The Beasts Within\"|medium=DVD featurette|publisher=BBC|date=2002}}</ref> In \"Next of Kin\", extreme close-ups of ''Australopithecus'' also employed actors wearing prosthetics.<ref>{{cite video|title=Production Interviews|medium=DVD featurette|people=Tim Haines|date=2002|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n\"Sabre Tooth\" was shot in Brazil, where ''Smilodon'' actually roamed.<ref>{{cite web|date=2001|archivedate=2001-12-14|title= Making Of - Model Making|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011214114548/http://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/models/index.shtml|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/beasts/makingof/models/index.shtml|publisher=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Filming of the [[Last glacial period|ice age]] landscapes for the final episode took place in Canada's [[Yukon Territory]].\n\n==List of episodes==\n===''Walking with Beasts''===\n[[BBC One]] aired the series weekly on Thursday nights, with a regular of repeats the following Sunday afternoon. In 2010, the series was repeated on [[BBC Three]] in [[Omnibus (broadcast)|omnibus]] format, as three hour-long episodes.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00sndkw Walking with Beasts -  Compilations - Episode 1] ''bbc.co.uk.'' Web. Retrieved 19 September 2018.</ref>\n\n<div style=\"width:75%;\">\n{{Episode table |background=#2155B0 |overall= |title= |aux1= |director= |airdate= |viewers= |country=U.K. |aux1T=Time |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 1\n| Title= New Dawn\n| RTitle= <ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0095rlk Walking with Beasts -  New Dawn] ''bbc.co.uk.'' Web. Retrieved 19 September 2018.</ref>\n| Aux1= 49 mya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|15|df=y}}\n| Viewers= 13.99<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/weekly-top-30/|title=Weekly top 30 programmes|publisher=BARB|access-date= 19 September 2018}}</ref><ref group=note>7 day data, including the original Thursday broadcast and Sunday repeat for the six main episodes.</ref>\n| ShortSummary=:'''49 million years ago, Early Eocene (Germany)'''\n:Filming location: [[Java]]\n[[File:Gastornis Walking With Beasts.jpg|thumb|''[[Gastornis]]'' as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']]\nThe episode starts by showing how the dinosaurs were dominating the land and that mammals were small. Then it shows how [[Chicxulub impactor|\"an asteroid the size of Mount Everest\"]] struck the Earth and [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event|demolished the dinosaurs]], and how mammals evolved into new forms thereafter.  The first episode depicts the warm tropical world of the early [[Eocene]], sixteen million years after the [[extinction]] of the non-avian dinosaurs. Birds, the surviving lineage of the dinosaurs, including the giant carnivorous ''[[Gastornis]]'', rule this world, while mammals are still very small. The setting is near the [[Messel pit]] in [[Germany]]. Due to volcanic activity, sudden bulk escapes of [[carbon dioxide]] trapped underneath lakes pose a significant hazard to the local wildlife. The episode centers around a ''[[Leptictidium]]'' family, a leaping, shrew-like mammal, which has emerged in the dawn hours to forage for food. As the mother ''Leptictidium'' forages, first in solidarity, and then with her pups, she wanders near a large predatory mammal, identified as an ''[[Ambulocetus]]'', a \"walking whale\". Despite its crocodilian similarity, the ''Ambulocetus'' is shown swimming by [[Evolution of cetaceans|caudal undulation]] like a modern cetacean.\nA female ''Gastornis'', who has been taking care of the single egg in her nest, makes two attempts to hunt a small herd of ''[[Eurohippus|Propalaeotherium]]'', early horses. The first attempt fails when sounds among the vegetation betray her presence. The second attack proves successful when the ''Propalaeotherium'' consume fermenting grapes and are unable to evade her attack. The ''Gastornis'' also defends her territory from another ''Gastornis''. Unfortunately, while the mother hunts, a horde of ''[[Titanomyrma]]'', giant carnivorous [[ants]], encounter the egg when it was just starting to hatch, and successfully kill and eat the chick. When the female discovers her dead offspring at dusk she leaves the forest to try and start another family.\n\nWith the arrival of night, a band of lemur-like ''[[Godinotia]]'', socialize and copulate in the dark. ''Ambulocetus'' finally manages to catch a [[Creodonta|creodont]] near the lake edge. As the night wears on, an earth tremor unleashes trapped carbon dioxide out from underneath the lake and the gas suffocates most of the surrounding life. The ''Leptictidium'' survive because the nest was upwind of the gas, and ''Gastornis'' also survived because she left that area in the forest.\n\nIt is mentioned that although the ''Leptictidium'' survived the gas, they would ultimately leave no descendants, while the ''Ambulocetus'', who was killed by the lethal gases, would evolve into the whales, hereby setting the scene for the next episode.\n\n'''Animals:'''\n''[[Leptictidium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Gastornis]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Ambulocetus]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Eurohippus|Propalaeotherium]]'' <ref group=note>Specimen featured in episode was based on ''Propaleotherium parvulum'' which is now considered to be synonymous with ''Eurohippus''</ref>\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Godinotia]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Eurotamandua]]'' (unnamed, live-acted by a [[tamandua]])\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Titanomyrma]]'' (unnamed, identified as giant ants)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Lesmesodon]]'' (unnamed)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Crocodile]]''\n{{\u00b7}}[[Gecko]]\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Tyrannosaurus]]'' (stock footage from ''[[Walking with Dinosaurs]]'')\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Ankylosaurus]]'' (stock footage from ''[[Walking with Dinosaurs]]'')\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Didelphodon]]'' (stock footage from ''[[Walking with Dinosaurs]]'')\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 2\n| Title= Whale Killer\n| Aux1= 36 mya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|22|df=y}}\n| Viewers= 11.34\n| ShortSummary= :'''36 million years ago, Late Eocene (Pakistan/Tethys Sea)'''\n:Filming location: [[Florida]]\n[[File:Andrewsarchus head model.jpg|thumb|''[[Andrewsarchus]]'' as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']]\nThe second episode is set in late [[Eocene]], when the [[polar caps]] froze over and drastically changed the Earth's [[ocean currents]] and [[climate]]. The first part of the episode explains how an early [[whale]], ''[[Basilosaurus]]'' mates and how the world is changing into an ocean [[famine]]. On land there is an ''[[Andrewsarchus]]'' driven to the beach to feed on [[sea turtle]]s. The narrator explains that ''Andrewsarchus'', the largest land mammal [[predator]] ever to walk the earth, has hooves and is related to sheep, so it is, in a sense, a \"sheep in wolf's clothing\". Back in the ocean, a starving mother ''Basilosaurus'' is forced to hunt in the [[mangrove]] swamps of [[Africa]], which will later become the [[Sahara Desert]]. Unable to catch a primate called ''[[Apidium]]'' due to a [[Physogaleus|shark]] killing one of the primates and spooking the others, she is then hunting a lone ''[[Moeritherium]]''. The ''Moeritherium'' crawls on to land, but in the mangroves, land does not last long. However the ''Moeritherium'' escapes and the ''Basilosaurus'' returns to the sea. The cast moves on to land where a herd of ''[[Embolotherium]]'' struggle to survive: one of their calves dies after birth and two ''Andrewsarchus'' feast on it, but the mother ''Embolotherium'' drives them away because she has a strong bond with her offspring, even if it is dead. Back in the sea, the mother ''Basilosaurus'' preys on a group of [[Dolphin]]-like ''[[Dorudon]]'' and their young, and is successful. The episode ends with the mother ''Basilosaurus'' swimming with her newborn calf.\n\nIt is acknowledged in the end that soon Africa will be pulled closer to Europe, causing the [[Tethys Sea]] to disappear. While whales as a whole will survive [[Eocene-Oligocene extinction event|the ensuing extinction]], ''Basilosaurus'', unfortunately, will disappear with the Tethys as well.\n\n'''Animals:'''\n''[[Basilosaurus]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Andrewsarchus]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Embolotherium]]'' (identified as brontothere)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Dorudon]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Moeritherium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Apidium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Physogaleus]]'' (identified as shark)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Puppigerus]]'' (identified as turtle)\n{{\u00b7}}[[Vulture]]\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 3\n| Title= Land of Giants\n| Aux1= 25  mya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|29|df=y}}\n| Viewers= 9.27\n| ShortSummary= :'''25 million years ago, Late Oligocene (Mongolia)'''\n:Filming location: [[Mexico]], [[Arizona]]\n[[File:Entelodon Walking With Beasts.jpg|thumb|''[[Entelodon]]'' as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']]\nThe third episode takes place during the late [[Oligocene]], in [[Mongolia]], where there were seasonal [[Rain|rains]] followed by a long [[drought]]. It focuses on a mother ''[[Paraceratherium]]'', a massive hornless [[rhinoceros]], the largest land mammal to ever live as one night, she gives birth to a healthy male calf, while trying to fend off the predatory ''[[Hyaenodon]]''. By morning, the calf slowly learns how to walk and after a week, his mother takes him out to the open plain where he will spend the rest of his life. The inquisitive calf runs into a mother ''[[Cynodictis]]'', who drives him out of her family burrow to protect her pups. The calf then learns to survive on his own, by copying his mother's actions. Not long after, his mother's previous calf arrives, but the mother violently repels him. A ''Hyaenodon'' is then seen stalking a herd of ''[[Chalicotherium]]'', successfully killing one, but a trio of ''[[Entelodon]]'' drive it off the carcass. During the dry season, there is a huge shortage of food and water, putting even the hardiest to their greatest stress. The mother, now dehydrated, has not been able to produce enough milk for the calf, who's getting weaker and weaker as time progresses. At night, the pair are joined by an older female, who leads them to a small, muddy lake, where they drink their fill and gain back their strength. The wet season returns, the water levels rise, flooding the ''Cynodictis'' family burrow, and drowning the sleeping pups. The mother and calf have to cross a river, the mother making it with ease, while the calf struggled to make it up a muddy bank, but he finally succeeded. 3 years pass, and the calf is furiously chased away by his mother. He then was not seen for days, but when he was seen, he was limping and had a leg injury, possibly caused by another young male ''Paraceratherium''. When he returned to his mother, she aggressively chased him away, as she now has a new calf to nurture. After 3 months, the calf learns how to stand on his own two feet and successfully drives away an ''Entelodon''.\n\n'''Animals:'''\n''[[Paraceratherium]]'' (identified as indricothere)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Hyaenodon]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Entelodon]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Chalicotherium]]'' (identified as chalicothere)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Cynodictis]]'' (identified as bear-dog)<ref>{{cite book\n | last = Haines\n | first = Tim\n | authorlink = Tim Haines\n | title = The Complete Guide to Prehistoric Life\n | url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781554071258\n | url-access = registration\n | publisher = Firefly Books\n | location = Canada\n | date = 2006\n | page = [https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781554071258/page/176 176]\n | isbn = 1-55407-125-9}}\n</ref>\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 4\n| Title= Next of Kin\n| Aux1= 3.2  mya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|12|6|df=y}}\n| Viewers= - <ref group=note>This episode did not reach the Top 30 programmes.</ref>\n| ShortSummary= :'''3.2 million years ago, Late Pliocene (Ethiopia)'''\n:Filming location: [[South Africa]], [[Ethiopia]]\n[[File:Walk With Beasts exhibition Ancylotherium model.jpg|thumb|''[[Ancylotherium]]'' as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']] \nThe fourth episode takes place in the [[Great Rift Valley, Ethiopia|Great Rift Valley]] in northeastern [[Africa]] of the late [[Pliocene]]. The climate has changed, and now great grasslands have replaced trees, with many modern-day animals appearing with them. The episode focuses around a tribe of small [[hominid]]s known as ''[[Australopithecus]]'', one of the first [[ape]]s able to walk upright and a close ancestor to [[humans]]. The ''Australopithecus'' has evolved to walk upright so as to better manoeuvre the plains as well as the climb the trees. However, it notes that although the ''Australopithecus'' looks human, it still only has a brain the size of a [[Common chimpanzee|chimpanzee]]'s. Some of the topics explored in the episode are the close social bonds among the [[tribe]], how they use [[Social grooming|grooming]] as a means of [[communication]], and how they work together to forage for food and to defend one another from attacks from such animals as an angry male ''[[Deinotherium]]'', an ancestor of the modern [[elephant]] which they have to run from to avoid being crushed, and the [[Felidae|feline]] predator ''[[Dinofelis]]''. It touches upon how competing tribes of ''Australopithecus'' war among one another, although most of the fighting is for show. It also explains the [[hierarchy]] in the tribe among the males, who are much larger than the females, and tells a story of how the dominating male nicknamed Grey is eventually overcome by another male nicknamed Hercules, who wins the right to feed first at a carrion and to mate with the females. The main story tells of a young ''Australopithecus'' nicknamed Blue whose mother has been killed by malaria. He and his tribe are later forced to flee their homeland during a fight over a waterhole with a rival tribe. After a long journey in search of a new home, Blue fits into his tribe by rallying them into scaring off a hungry ''Dinofelis''.\n\n'''Animals:'''\n''[[Australopithecus]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Dinofelis]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Deinotherium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Ancylotherium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}[[Common warthog]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[White rhinoceros]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Black-backed jackal]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[White-backed vulture]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Zebra]] (carcass)\n{{\u00b7}}[[Ostrich]] (egg)\n\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 5\n| Title= Sabre Tooth\n| Aux1= 1 mya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|12|13|df=y}}\n| Viewers= 5.87\n| ShortSummary= :'''1 million years ago, Early Pleistocene (Paraguay)'''\n:Filming location: [[Brazil]]\n[[File:Phorusrhacos - Walk With Beasts.jpg|thumb|''[[Phorusrhacos]]'' as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']]\nThe fifth episode shows the strange [[fauna]] of the isolated continent of [[South America]] and explores the effects of the [[Great American Interchange]], which had happened 1.5 million years earlier. Since South America had drifted apart from [[Antarctica]] 30 million years ago, many unique [[mammals]] had evolved, including the ''[[Doedicurus]]'', an armoured [[armadillo]]-like mammal with a cannon ball-sized spiked club on its tail; the ''[[Macrauchenia]],'' a [[camel]]-like mammal with a long trunk; and the ''[[Megatherium]]'', a giant [[ground sloth]]. Before the continents of South America and [[North America]] collided, a 10-foot-tall predatory [[Phorusrhacidae|terror bird]] called ''[[Phorusrhacos]]'', had reigned as [[top predator]]. However, the great cats migrating from the north, soon displaced them as top predators. The episode focuses on a male ''[[Smilodon]],'' a [[sabre-toothed cat]], called Half Tooth, whose leadership of a [[pride]] is threatened by two rival males who are brothers and work together against him. Half Tooth wisely backs off without any serious injuries, feeling that the rival males would be too strong for him. The rival males kill Half Tooth's cubs, and take over his pride. Next, the episode shows the ''Smilodon'' hunting down ''Macrauchenia'' and trying to protect the remaining two young from the two males. In the background, ''Phorusrhacos'' wait to scavenge the ''Macrauchenia'', which the pride of ''Smilodon''  have killed. However, a ''Megatherium'' charges the ''Smilodon'', in order to eat some of the carrion as a diet supplement. In the process, the ''Megatherium'' kills the dominant rival male, enabling Half Tooth to return, kill the other male and reclaim his territory. A year later, his mate has another litter of cubs.\n\n'''Animals:'''\n''[[Smilodon]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Phorusrhacos]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Macrauchenia]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Megatherium]]''\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Doedicurus]]''\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 6\n| Title= Mammoth Journey\n| Aux1=  30,000 ya\n| DirectedBy=Jasper James & Nigel Paterson\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|12|20|df=y}}\n| Viewers= 9.48\n| ShortSummary= :'''30,000 years ago, Late Pleistocene (Belgium)'''\n:Filming location: [[Yukon]]\n[[File:Woolly Rhinoceros Hunt.jpg|thumb|[[Woolly rhinoceros]] as it appeared in ''Walking with Beasts'']]\nThe sixth episode takes place during the last [[Ice Age]] of the late [[Pleistocene]]. It starts in the peak of the summer. The [[North Sea]] has become a [[Doggerland|grassy plain]] because the ice at the polar caps has caused the [[sea level]]s to drop significantly. Grazing on the plain are herds of [[woolly mammoth]]s, [[saiga antelope]]s, and [[bison]]. A clan of [[Cro-Magnon]] is also there spending the summer. The central focus of the episode is the migration of the herd of mammoths as they travel 400 kilometres from the North Sea to the [[Swiss Alps]] for the winter and then back again in the spring. As the mammoth herd migrates south, the episode shows two large [[deer]], the [[elk]]-like ''[[Irish elk|Megaloceros]]'', fighting for rights to a [[harem]] of females. As the male elk fight, a group of Cro-Magnons ambushes them and kills one. A mother mammoth and her baby are separated from the herd, but survive an encounter with a [[Panthera leo spelaea|European cave lion]]. When the herd of mammoths reaches the Swiss Alps, the mother and baby mammoth reunite with their herd. The episode also depicts a clan of [[Neanderthal]]s, who have especially evolved to survive in the cold climate. One is charged by a [[woolly rhinoceros]], but escapes, in part because of his stocky constitution. The climax of the episode is when the clan of Neanderthals attack the herd of mammoth as they turn back to the north. The Neanderthals are gifted hunters who are able to chase two mammoths off a cliff by using [[fire]] and spears, one of them being the matriarch of the herd. The episode ends in the [[Oxford University Museum of Natural History]] with people looking at various [[skeleton]]s of some descendants of the animals featured in the series. The camera then pulls back through the roof of the [[museum]] until the whole world is visible. The narrator states that, \"We have since built museums to celebrate the past, and spent decades studying prehistoric lives. And if all this has taught us anything, it is this: no species lasts forever.\"\n\n'''Animals:'''\n[[Woolly Mammoth]] \n{{\u00b7}}''[[Irish elk|Megaloceros]]''\n{{\u00b7}}[[Woolly Rhinoceros]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Cro-Magnon]] (identified as humans)\n{{\u00b7}}''[[Panthera spelaea]]'' (identified as cave lion)\n{{\u00b7}}[[Neanderthal]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Saiga antelope]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Wolf]]\n{{\u00b7}}[[Wisent]]\n\n|LineColor = 2155B0\n}}\n}}\n</div>\n\n===''The Science of Walking with Beasts''===\nA two-episode companion documentary, ''The Science of Walking with Beasts'', aired in November 2001 on [[BBC One]]. This series featured interviews with palaeontologists and explanations of how the fossil record and modern day descendants have informed what is known about the animals depicted in ''Beasts'', as well as brief sections showing the development of the CGI and animatronic animals used in the series.\n\n{{Episode table |background=FFFF00 |overall= |title= |director= |airdate= |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 1\n| Title= Triumph of the Beasts\n| DirectedBy=Kate Bartlett\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|21|df=y}}\n| ShortSummary= An explanation of how mammals evolved to be larger and more prevalent, eventually taking the dinosaurs' place as some of the most successful creatures on the planet. The [[Messel pit]] fossil site and fossil discoveries of [[Roy Chapman Andrews]] are featured.\n|LineColor = FFFF00 \n}}{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber= 2\n| Title= The Beasts Within\n| DirectedBy=Nigel Paterson \n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|28|df=y}}\n| ShortSummary= An explanation of how prehistoric apes evolved into modern man, and which attributes made human ancestors so successful. The [[La Cotte de St Brelade]] site is featured.\n}}\n}}\n\n==Release==\n''Walking with Beasts'' was originally broadcast in the United Kingdom on the [[BBC1]] from 12 November to 21 December 2001. In North America, it aired on December 9, 2001 on the [[Discovery Channel]]. The UK broadcast was the first non-sports BBC interactive programme.<ref>{{cite news|title=Digital Evolution for BBC Beasts|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/oct/09/newmedia.broadcasting|newspaper=The Guardian|last=Gibson|first=Owen|date=2001-10-09}}</ref>\n''Beasts'' was released on [[VHS]] on 26 November 2001. A DVD release came the next year on 12 February for North America (as ''Walking with Prehistoric Beasts'') and 8 April in the United Kingdom. The North American release restores the original narration by Kenneth Branagh. The DVD contains several special features: two 50-minute documentaries on prehistoric life, \"Triumph of the Beasts\" (about Cenozoic life at large) and \"The Beasts Within\" (which focuses on the humans and primates in the show); interviews with Tim Haines; animated storyboards; a photo gallery; and several fact files on the animals featured in the series. This edition was bundled with ''The Complete Walking with... Collection'' which came out on 23 July 2002.\n\nA re-edited and re-narrated version of ''Beasts'' was presented as the second season of ''[[Prehistoric Planet]]'', a [[Discovery Kids]] programme intended for a younger audience than ''Walking with...''\n\n===Promotion===\n''Beasts'' was promoted with a breakfast cereal tie-in from Kellogg's and the video game ''Walking with Beasts: Operation Salvage'' for Windows PCs.<ref>{{cite web|title=65 Million Years of Strategy|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2001/10/05/65-million-years-of-strategy|website=IGN|date=2001-10-05}}</ref> The soundtrack by [[Ben Bartlett]] was released on [[CD]]. An exhibition took place at the [[Herbert Art Gallery and Museum]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Winner of competition for Walking with Beasts exhibition at Coventry's The Herbert|newspaper=Coventry Telegraph|date=2001-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe first episode of ''Walking with Beasts'' attracted an audience of 8.5 million, 35 per cent of television viewers at that time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Munching with Beasts|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/2743440/Munching-with-Beasts.html|date=2001-11-27|last=Mills|first=Dominic|newspaper=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nCritics generally enjoyed ''Walking with Beasts''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-481264.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911161220/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-481264.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-09-11|title=Walking with Prehistoric Beasts|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=2001-12-09|last=Zad|first=Martie}}{{Subscription|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> However, there were some complaints about overbearing narration and disappointing visual effects.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/16/firstnight.broadcasting|title=First night: walking with beasts|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===Companion book===\nA companion book was written by [[Tim Haines]] to accompany the first screening of the series in 2001. As with ''Walking with Dinosaurs'', the written version of ''Walking with Beasts'' elaborated on the background for each story, went further in explaining the science on which much of the programme as based, and included descriptions of several animals not identified or featured in the series.<ref>{{cite book|last=Haines|first=Tim|title=Walking with Beasts: A Prehistoric Safari|publisher=DK Publishing|date=2001|ISBN=0789478293|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/walkingwithbeast00hain}}</ref>\n\n==Scientific accuracy==\nIn the first episode, the ''[[Gastornis]]'' are depicted as carnivorous predators, which is in agreement with their perception at the time as \"terror birds.\" However, in 2013, a scientific study suggested that the bird was probably omnivorous or a herbivore.<ref>{{cite web|last=Viegas|first=Jennifer|url=http://www.abc.net.au/science/articles/2013/08/30/3837440.htm?site=science/talkingscience&topic=ancient|title='Terror bird' was scary-looking vegetarian|publisher=''ABC Science''|date=August 30, 2013|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Ambulocetus]]'' is depicted as amphibious; later studies suggest that it was fully aquatic.<ref name=\"aquatic2016\">{{cite journal | first1 = K. | last1 = Ando | first2 = S.-I. | last2 = Fujiwara | title = Farewell to life on land \u2013 thoracic strength as a new indicator to determine paleoecology in secondary aquatic mammals | doi = 10.1111/joa.12518 | journal = Journal of Anatomy | volume = 229 | issue = 6 | date = 2016 | pages = 768\u2013777}}</ref> ''Ambulocetus'' lived in Pakistan, not Germany.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Paleotology database|url=https://paleobiodb.org/classic/basicCollectionSearch?a=basicCollectionSearch&collection_no=49002|title=H-GSP 9210 (Eocene of Pakistan)}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nThe series won an [[Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program (for Programming One Hour or More)|Outstanding Animated Program]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*''[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sn/prehistoric_life/tv_radio/wwbeasts/ Walking with Beasts - BBC Science & Nature]''\n*{{IMDb title|0286285|title=Walking with Prehistoric Beasts}}\n*''[https://web.archive.org/web/20050527095948/http://www.abc.net.au/beasts/ Walking with Beasts]'' at [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]\n\n{{Walking with}}\n{{EmmyAward AnimationLessThanHour 2001\u20132025}}\n{{Impossible Pictures}}\n{{BBC Natural History Unit}}\n\n[[Category:2001 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2001 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000s British television series]]\n[[Category:BBC television documentaries]]\n[[Category:Discovery Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about prehistoric life]]\n[[Category:Television series about mammals]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program winners]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (television series)]]\n[[Category:Walking with...]]\n", "name_user": "71.105.125.34", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eWalking with Beasts)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walking_with_Beasts"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Camp Allegheny", "text_new": "<!-- {{more footnotes|date=February 2010}} -->\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Camp Allegheny<br/>(Battle of Allegheny Mountain)\n|image=[[Image:Camp Allegheny-Battlefield.jpg|300px|Camp Allegheny Battlefield]]\n|caption=Battlefield along [[Allegheny Mountain (West Virginia, Virginia)|Allegheny Mountain]]\n|partof=the [[American Civil War]]\n|date= {{Start date|1861|12|13}}\n|place=[[Pocahontas County, West Virginia|Pocahontas County, Virginia]] (now [[West Virginia]])\n|result= Inconclusive<ref name=\"ABPP\" />\n|combatant1= {{flagicon|USA|1861}} [[United States]] ([[Union (American Civil War)|Union]])\n|combatant2= {{flagicon|CSA|1861}} [[Confederate States of America|CSA (Confederacy)]]\n|commander1=[[Robert Milroy]]\n|commander2=[[Edward Johnson (general)|Edward Johnson]]\n|strength1=Brigades\n|strength2=Brigades\n|casualties1=137\n|casualties2=146\n|coordinates = {{coord|38|28|26|N|79|43|28|W|display=inline,title|name=Camp Allegheny}}\n}}\n\n{{Campaignbox Operations in Western Virginia}}\nThe '''Battle of Camp Allegheny''', also known as the '''Battle of [[Allegheny Mountain (West Virginia, Virginia)|Allegheny Mountain]]''', took place on December 13, 1861, in [[Pocahontas County, West Virginia|Pocahontas County, Virginia]] (now [[West Virginia]]), about 3 miles from the mountainous border of [[Highland County, Virginia]], as part of the Operations in Western Virginia Campaign during the [[American Civil War]].<ref name=\"ABPP\" />  The battle was a small brigade-level conflict, and while the Confederates technically won with a Union withdrawal, it was considered militarily indecisive.  However, it was a critical battle for the future border of Virginia and West Virginia, ensuring Highland County remained in Confederate hands and not involved in the formation of the future state of West Virginia<ref>https://www.richmond.com/special-section/battle-shaped-destiny-of-virginia-west-virginia/article_228cc12d-12a6-57cb-bdff-815e4ff7364f.html?mode=jqm&alt=gal&pos=1</ref>. \n\n==Background==\nIn December, [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] forces under [[Colonel (United States)|Col.]] [[Edward Johnson (general)|Edward Johnson]] occupied the summit pass of Allegheny Mountain (roughly 4,400 feet above sea level)  to defend the  [[Staunton and Parkersburg Turnpike]] that offered a point of access from the mountains of western Virginia into the strategic Shenandoah Valley. The occupation of the high mountain pass coincided with a bitter winter, with much suffering and disease among the Southern troops<ref>https://www.virginia.org/listings/HistoricSites/CampAlleghenyConfederateOutpost/</ref>. Early Union victories in what is now West Virginia had solidified control in much of the western mountains of Virginia, emboldening a Union move to take the Staunton to Petersburg Pike<ref>https://www.battlefields.org/learn/civil-war/battles/camp-allegheny</ref>. Perhaps thinking that Confederate morale was low<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/191</ref>, a [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] brigade of 2,000 under [[Brigadier General|Brig. Gen.]] [[Robert H. Milroy]] attacked Johnson and his 1,200 Confederates at sunrise on December 13.<ref name=\"ABPP\" /><ref>https://www.battlefields.org/learn/civil-war/battles/camp-allegheny</ref>\n\n==Battle==\nMilroy's advance and a Confederate scouting party had skirmished on December 12. The next morning, Milroy divided his troops into a two pronged attack to flank the Confederate camp. The first column advanced up the Staunton-Parkersburg Pike, engaging the Confederate right side for several hours before withdrawing. Beause of the difficult mountain terrain, the second Union column arrived shortly after the withdrawal of the first column, unable to suuport the main body of Union troops on the right<ref>https://www.mycivilwar.com/battles/611213.html</ref>, but then attacked the Confederate left<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/191</ref>. \n\n[[File:Camp_Allegheny_Battlefield_West_Virginia.jpg|305px|thumb|right|Map of Camp Allegheny Battlefield core and study areas by the [[American Battlefield Protection Program]].]]\nIn a piercing winter wind, fighting raged for much of the sunny morning as each side maneuvered on the hillside slopes, fields and woods to gain the advantage. On the right flank, Milroy's strong force was in a mountain clearing, among the fallen timber, stumps and brush, which proved to be too difficult for the Confederate infantry to dislodge. A Confederate [[artillery|artillery battery]] unlimbered and unleashed a \"storm of round shot and canister among them, knocking their timber defences about their heads, and making their nest too hot to hold them...\" The fighting moved back and forth from advance to retreat, with the Union temporarily occupying the post, only to be driven off. The Confederates attempted their own flanking maneuvers which quickly failed because their force was too thin. The fighting was in such close quarters that eight of the Confederate cannons in the fortification could not be used<ref>https://www.mycivilwar.com/battles/611213.html</ref>.  After fighting for over seven hours<ref>https://emergingcivilwar.com/2012/11/24/a-historians-stroll-across-camp-allegheny/</ref> Milroy's troops finally withdrew, retreating to his camps at Green Spring Run near Cheat Mountain. Johnson's losses were high: 25 men were killed and 97 were wounded in the engagement, plus 23 went missing.\n\nAccording to one Confederate soldier in the [[52nd Virginia Infantry]]:<ref name=\"JSR\" />\n<blockquote>I had a splendid position in this battle and could see the whole fight without having to take any part in it, and I remember how I thought Colonel Johnson must be the most wonderful hero in the world, as I saw him at one point, where his men were hard pressed, snatch a musket in one hand and, swinging a big club in the other, he led his line right up among the enemy, driving them headlong down the mountain, killing and wounding many with the bayonet and capturing a large number of prisoners...</blockquote>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe battle, though considered insignificant compared to later battles in the Civil War, was actually one of the bloodiest in the initial year of the war<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/191</ref>. The Union casualties are estimated at 137 and Confederate casualities at 147<ref>https://www.battlefields.org/learn/civil-war/battles/camp-allegheny</ref>. Johnson would receive the nickname \"Allegheny\" Johnson for his role at the battle and for commanding the forbidding mountainous Camp Allegheny post. \n\nIronically, the Confederates had received orders to withdraw a few days prior to the battle<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/191</ref>. But the failed Union advance convinced the Confederate higher command to reinforce Johnson\u2019s force in place at Camp Allegheny with five regiments through the remainder of the harsh winter of 1861\u201362<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/191</ref><ref>http://www.civilwar.com/history/battles/battle-summaries-19937/148062-camp-alleghany.html</ref>. The snow was often knee to waist deep. The toll on the Confederate troops was brutal. In March 18, 1862, prior to the subsequent [[Battle of McDowell]] in Highland County (May 8, 1862,) Johnson, by then promoted to General, had roughly 4,000 men stationed at Camp Allegheny in Pocahontas County, but his effective strength was only 2,784, as nearly 1,200 men were sick or unavailable<ref>http://www.shenandoahatwar.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/McDowell-Battlefield-Driving-Tour.pdf</ref>. \n\nAfter the Battle of Camp Allegheny, Johnson also knew that the post was vulnerable to being flanked, and believed that  Shenandoah Mountain, 40 miles to the southeast, was a better position to defend the Staunton to Parkerburg Pike and Shenandoah Valley. Combined with the loss of men in the bitter mountain weather and the logistical challenges of keeping the remote mountain post effectively supplied, [[General Robert E. Lee]] agreed to let Johnson abandon the post in favor of Shenandoah Mountain on April 2, 1862<ref>https://www.battlefields.org/visit/heritage-sites/camp-allegheny</ref>. By April 6, 1862, Johnson's constructed [[Fort Edward Johnson]] at the site on Shenandoah Mountain, 26 miles west of Staunton. The new fortification was soon abandoned on April 19, when Johnson left to rendezvous with [[Gen. Thomas \"Stonewall\"Jackson]] in advance of the Battle of McDowell.\n\nThe battles in the rugged and mountainous region of western Virginia were small by later standards but left an enduring footprint because those counties that were in Union control formed the nucleus of the new state of West Virginia. Because of the Battle of Camp Allegheny (and the subsequent Battle of McDowell,) the future state line between Virginia and West Virginia would begin and stop at the Pocohantas and Highland County line, even though the counties shared the same geographic traits and mountain culture. Pocohantas County would remained in Union Control, Highland County in Confederate hands. As a result, Highland County would not participate in the councils and voting for secession to West Virginia, but continued as part of the state of Virginia<ref>https://www.richmond.com/special-section/battle-shaped-destiny-of-virginia-west-virginia/article_228cc12d-12a6-57cb-bdff-815e4ff7364f.html?mode=jqm&alt=gal&pos=1</ref>.\n\nIn 1903, Ambrose Bierce wrote a column in The New York American about the visiting the battle site, entitled \"A Bivouac of the Dead<ref>http://www.online-literature.com/bierce/765/</ref>,\" recalling his involvement in the battle as a member of a Union regiment. Bierce wrote movingly about the sacrifice and suffering of the men in this little remembered battle in a remote area, and hauntingly about how little the battlefield had changed<ref>http://www.ambrosebierce.org/journal1owens.html</ref>.\n\n==Camp Allegheny Historic District==\n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Camp Allegheny\n  | embed =no\n  | nrhp_type = hd  | nocat = yes\n  | image = \n  | caption = \n  | location= County Route 3, just east of County Route 5 at Top of Allegheny, near [[Bartow, West Virginia]]\n  | locmapin = West Virginia#USA\n  | map_width = 305\n  | built = 1861\n  | architecture = \n  | added = September 28, 1990\n  | area = 105 acres\n  | governing_body = Federal \n  | refnum = 90001446<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Camp Allegheny Historic District''' is a national [[Historic district (United States)|historic district]] encompassing one contributing structure and four contributing sites.  They are the earthworks, site of hut and campground, cemetery, church site, and the site of the Yeager farmstead.<ref name=\"dhr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wvculture.org/shpo/nr/pdf/pocahontas/90001446.pdf|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory Nomination Form: Camp Allegheny|date=November 1989|accessdate=2011-09-01 |author=Kim A. McBride|publisher=State of West Virginia, West Virginia Division of Culture and History, Historic Preservation}}</ref>\n\nIt was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1990.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Monongahela National Forest]]\n*[[White Top]] \u2014 site of Union Army camp several miles west on [[Cheat Mountain]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"ABPP\">{{cite web|title=Battle Summary|url=https://www.nps.gov/abpp/battles/wv008.htm|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"JSR\">{{cite book|last1=Robson|first1=John S|title=How a One-Legged Rebel Lives: Reminiscences of the Civil War: The Story of the Campaigns of Stonewall Jackson, as Told by a High Private in the \"Foot Cavalry\"|date=1898|publisher=The Educator Co|location=Durham NC|pages=20\u20131|url=http://docsouth.unc.edu:80/robson/robson.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050923091734/http://docsouth.unc.edu/robson/robson.html|url-status = dead|archive-date=2005-09-23|accessdate=12 December 2016|df=}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Geiger, Joe Jr. ''Holding the Line: The Battle of Allegheny Mountain and Confederate Defense of the Staunton-Parkersburg Turnpike, 1861-1862''. Charleston, WV: Quarrier Press, 2012.\n* Woodward, Eddie. \"An Affair of Outposts: The Battle of Alleghany Mountain,\" ''West Virginia History'' 59: 1-35 (2003).\n* Woodward, Eddie. \"Crashing the Party: Alcohol & Alcohol Abuse within the Confederate Army of the Northwest,\" ''Civil War Times Illustrated'' 40(6): 48-54 (December 2001).\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Battle of Camp Allegheny}}\n* [http://www.wvculture.org/history/civilwar/alleghenymountain01.html Battle of Allegheny Mountain] ''West Virginia Legislative Hand Book'', 1928, West Virginia Archives and History\n* [http://vimeo.com/6993373 Video tour of Camp Allegheny battlefield]\n\n{{Monongahela National Forest}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allegheny, Battle of Camp Allegheny}}\n[[Category:Battles of the American Civil War in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Parks on the National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Western Virginia Campaign]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Eastern Theater of the American Civil War|Camp Allegheny]]\n[[Category:Inconclusive battles of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Pocahontas County, West Virginia in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Pocahontas County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:1861 in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:1861 in Virginia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Pocahontas County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Conflict sites on the National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Battlefields of the Eastern Theater of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:December 1861 events]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- {{more footnotes|date=February 2010}} -->\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Camp Allegheny<br/>(Battle of Allegheny Mountain)\n|image=[[Image:Camp Allegheny-Battlefield.jpg|300px|Camp Allegheny Battlefield]]\n|caption=Battlefield along [[Allegheny Mountain (West Virginia, Virginia)|Allegheny Mountain]]\n|partof=the [[American Civil War]]\n|date= {{Start date|1861|12|13}}\n|place=[[Pocahontas County, West Virginia|Pocahontas County, Virginia]] (now [[West Virginia]])\n|result= Inconclusive<ref name=\"ABPP\" />\n|combatant1= {{flagicon|USA|1861}} [[United States]] ([[Union (American Civil War)|Union]])\n|combatant2= {{flagicon|CSA|1861}} [[Confederate States of America|CSA (Confederacy)]]\n|commander1=[[Robert Milroy]]\n|commander2=[[Edward Johnson (general)|Edward Johnson]]\n|strength1=Brigades\n|strength2=Brigades\n|casualties1=137\n|casualties2=146\n|coordinates = {{coord|38|28|26|N|79|43|28|W|display=inline,title|name=Camp Allegheny}}\n}}\n\n{{Campaignbox Operations in Western Virginia}}\nThe '''Battle of Camp Allegheny''', also known as the '''Battle of [[Allegheny Mountain (West Virginia, Virginia)|Allegheny Mountain]]''', took place on December 13, 1861, in [[Pocahontas County, West Virginia|Pocahontas County, Virginia]] (now [[West Virginia]]), about 3 miles from the mountainous border of [[Highland County, Virginia]], as part of the Operations in Western Virginia Campaign during the [[American Civil War]].<ref name=\"ABPP\" />  The battle was a small brigade-level conflict, and while the Confederates technically won with a Union withdrawal, it was considered militarily indecisive.  However, it was a critical battle for the future border of Virginia and West Virginia, ensuring Highland County remained in Confederate hands and not involved in the formation of the future state of West Virginia<ref>https://www.richmond.com/special-section/battle-shaped-destiny-of-virginia-west-virginia/article_228cc12d-12a6-57cb-bdff-815e4ff7364f.html?mode=jqm&alt=gal&pos=1</ref>. \n\n==Background==\nIn December, [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] forces under [[Colonel (United States)|Col.]] [[Edward Johnson (general)|Edward Johnson]] occupied the summit pass of Allegheny Mountain (roughly 4,400 feet above sea level)  to defend the  [[Staunton and Parkersburg Turnpike]] that offered a point of access from the mountains of western Virginia into the strategic Shenandoah Valley. The occupation of the high mountain pass coincided with a bitter winter, with much suffering and disease among the Southern troops<ref>https://www.virginia.org/listings/HistoricSites/CampAlleghenyConfederateOutpost/</ref>. Early Union victories in what is now West Virginia had solidified control in much of the western mountains of Virginia, emboldening a Union move to take the Staunton to Petersburg Pike<ref>https://www.battlefields.org/learn/civil-war/battles/camp-allegheny</ref>. Perhaps thinking that Confederate morale was low<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/191</ref>, a [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] brigade of 2,000 under [[Brigadier General|Brig. Gen.]] [[Robert H. Milroy]] attacked Johnson and his 1,200 Confederates at sunrise on December 13.<ref name=\"ABPP\" /><ref>https://www.battlefields.org/learn/civil-war/battles/camp-allegheny</ref>\n\n==Battle==\nMilroy's advance and a Confederate scouting party had skirmished on December 12. The next morning, Milroy divided his troops into a two pronged attack to flank the Confederate camp. The first column advanced up the Staunton-Parkersburg Pike, engaging the Confederate right side for several hours before withdrawing. Beause of the difficult mountain terrain, the second Union column arrived shortly after the withdrawal of the first column, unable to suuport the main body of Union troops on the right<ref>https://www.mycivilwar.com/battles/611213.html</ref>, but then attacked the Confederate left<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/191</ref>. \n\n[[File:Camp_Allegheny_Battlefield_West_Virginia.jpg|305px|thumb|right|Map of Camp Allegheny Battlefield core and study areas by the [[American Battlefield Protection Program]].]]\nIn a piercing winter wind, fighting raged for much of the sunny morning as each side maneuvered on the hillside slopes, fields and woods to gain the advantage. On the right flank, Milroy's strong force was in a mountain clearing, among the fallen timber, stumps and brush, which proved to be too difficult for the Confederate infantry to dislodge. A Confederate [[artillery|artillery battery]] unlimbered and unleashed a \"storm of round shot and canister among them, knocking their timber defences about their heads, and making their nest too hot to hold them...\" The fighting moved back and forth from advance to retreat, with the Union temporarily occupying the post, only to be driven off. The Confederates attempted their own flanking maneuvers which quickly failed because their force was too thin. The fighting was in such close quarters that eight of the Confederate cannons in the fortification could not be used<ref>https://www.mycivilwar.com/battles/611213.html</ref>.  After fighting for over seven hours<ref>https://emergingcivilwar.com/2012/11/24/a-historians-stroll-across-camp-allegheny/</ref> Milroy's troops finally withdrew, retreating to his camps at Green Spring Run near Cheat Mountain. Johnson's losses were high: 25 men were killed and 97 were wounded in the engagement, plus 23 went missing.\n\nAccording to one Confederate soldier in the [[52nd Virginia Infantry]]:<ref name=\"JSR\" />\n<blockquote>I had a splendid position in this battle and could see the whole fight without having to take any part in it, and I remember how I thought Colonel Johnson must be the most wonderful hero in the world, as I saw him at one point, where his men were hard pressed, snatch a musket in one hand and, swinging a big club in the other, he led his line right up among the enemy, driving them headlong down the mountain, killing and wounding many with the bayonet and capturing a large number of prisoners...</blockquote>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe battle, though considered insignificant compared to later battles in the Civil War, was actually one of the bloodiest in the initial year of the war<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/191</ref>. The Union casualties are estimated at 137 and Confederate casualities at 147<ref>https://www.battlefields.org/learn/civil-war/battles/camp-allegheny</ref>. Johnson would receive the nickname \"Allegheny\" Johnson for his role at the battle and for commanding the forbidding mountainous Camp Allegheny post. \n\nIronically, the Confederates had received orders to withdraw a few days prior to the battle<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/191</ref>. But the failed Union advance convinced the Confederate higher command to reinforce Johnson\u2019s force in place at Camp Allegheny with five regiments through the remainder of the harsh winter of 1861\u201362<ref>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/191</ref><ref>http://www.civilwar.com/history/battles/battle-summaries-19937/148062-camp-alleghany.html</ref>. The snow was often knee to waist deep. The toll on the Confederate troops was brutal. In March 18, 1862, prior to the subsequent [[Battle of McDowell]] in Highland County (May 8, 1862,) Johnson, by then promoted to General, had roughly 4,000 men stationed at Camp Allegheny in Pocahontas County, but his effective strength was only 2,784, as nearly 1,200 men were sick or unavailable<ref>http://www.shenandoahatwar.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/McDowell-Battlefield-Driving-Tour.pdf</ref>. After the Battle of Camp Allegheny, Johnson also knew that the post was vulnerable to being flanked, and believed that  Shenandoah Mountain, 40 miles to the southeast, was a better position to defend the Staunton to Parkerburg Pike and Shenandoah Valley. Combined with the loss of men in the bitter mountain weather and the logistical challenges of keeping the remote mountain post effectively supplied, [[General Robert E. Lee]] agreed to let Johnson abandon the post in favor of Shenandoah Mountain on April 2, 1862<ref>https://www.battlefields.org/visit/heritage-sites/camp-allegheny</ref>. By April 6, 1862, Johnson's constructed [[Fort Edward Johnson]] at the site on Shenandoah Mountain, 26 miles west of Staunton. The new fortification was soon abandoned on April 19, when Johnson left to rendezvous with [[Gen. Thomas \"Stonewall\"Jackson]] in advance of the Battle of McDowell.\n\nThe battles in the rugged and mountainous region of western Virginia were small by later standards but left an enduring footprint because those counties that were in Union control formed the nucleus of the new state of West Virginia. Because of the Battle of Camp Allegheny (and the subsequent Battle of McDowell,) the future state line between Virginia and West Virginia would begin and stop at the Pocohantas and Highland County line, even though the counties shared the same geographic traits and mountain culture. Pocohantas County would remained in Union Control, Highland County in Confederate hands. As a result, Highland County would not participate in the councils and voting for secession to West Virginia, but continued as part of the state of Virginia<ref>https://www.richmond.com/special-section/battle-shaped-destiny-of-virginia-west-virginia/article_228cc12d-12a6-57cb-bdff-815e4ff7364f.html?mode=jqm&alt=gal&pos=1</ref>.\n\nIn 1903, Ambrose Bierce wrote a column in The New York American about the visiting the battle site, entitled \"A Bivouac of the Dead<ref>http://www.online-literature.com/bierce/765/</ref>,\" recalling his involvement in the battle as a member of a Union regiment. Bierce wrote movingly about the sacrifice and suffering of the men in this little remembered battle in a remote area, and hauntingly about how little the battlefield had changed<ref>http://www.ambrosebierce.org/journal1owens.html</ref>.\n\n==Camp Allegheny Historic District==\n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Camp Allegheny\n  | embed =no\n  | nrhp_type = hd  | nocat = yes\n  | image = \n  | caption = \n  | location= County Route 3, just east of County Route 5 at Top of Allegheny, near [[Bartow, West Virginia]]\n  | locmapin = West Virginia#USA\n  | map_width = 305\n  | built = 1861\n  | architecture = \n  | added = September 28, 1990\n  | area = 105 acres\n  | governing_body = Federal \n  | refnum = 90001446<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Camp Allegheny Historic District''' is a national [[Historic district (United States)|historic district]] encompassing one contributing structure and four contributing sites.  They are the earthworks, site of hut and campground, cemetery, church site, and the site of the Yeager farmstead.<ref name=\"dhr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wvculture.org/shpo/nr/pdf/pocahontas/90001446.pdf|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory Nomination Form: Camp Allegheny|date=November 1989|accessdate=2011-09-01 |author=Kim A. McBride|publisher=State of West Virginia, West Virginia Division of Culture and History, Historic Preservation}}</ref>\n\nIt was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1990.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Monongahela National Forest]]\n*[[White Top]] \u2014 site of Union Army camp several miles west on [[Cheat Mountain]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"ABPP\">{{cite web|title=Battle Summary|url=https://www.nps.gov/abpp/battles/wv008.htm|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"JSR\">{{cite book|last1=Robson|first1=John S|title=How a One-Legged Rebel Lives: Reminiscences of the Civil War: The Story of the Campaigns of Stonewall Jackson, as Told by a High Private in the \"Foot Cavalry\"|date=1898|publisher=The Educator Co|location=Durham NC|pages=20\u20131|url=http://docsouth.unc.edu:80/robson/robson.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050923091734/http://docsouth.unc.edu/robson/robson.html|url-status = dead|archive-date=2005-09-23|accessdate=12 December 2016|df=}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Geiger, Joe Jr. ''Holding the Line: The Battle of Allegheny Mountain and Confederate Defense of the Staunton-Parkersburg Turnpike, 1861-1862''. Charleston, WV: Quarrier Press, 2012.\n* Woodward, Eddie. \"An Affair of Outposts: The Battle of Alleghany Mountain,\" ''West Virginia History'' 59: 1-35 (2003).\n* Woodward, Eddie. \"Crashing the Party: Alcohol & Alcohol Abuse within the Confederate Army of the Northwest,\" ''Civil War Times Illustrated'' 40(6): 48-54 (December 2001).\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Battle of Camp Allegheny}}\n* [http://www.wvculture.org/history/civilwar/alleghenymountain01.html Battle of Allegheny Mountain] ''West Virginia Legislative Hand Book'', 1928, West Virginia Archives and History\n* [http://vimeo.com/6993373 Video tour of Camp Allegheny battlefield]\n\n{{Monongahela National Forest}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allegheny, Battle of Camp Allegheny}}\n[[Category:Battles of the American Civil War in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Parks on the National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Western Virginia Campaign]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Eastern Theater of the American Civil War|Camp Allegheny]]\n[[Category:Inconclusive battles of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Pocahontas County, West Virginia in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Pocahontas County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:1861 in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:1861 in Virginia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Pocahontas County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Conflict sites on the National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Ba